text: axial images and coronal images were obtained through the paranasal sinuses without the administration of iv contrast.no prior studies are available for comparison.there is mucosal thickening in the frontal and maxillary sinuses bilaterally as well as within the sphenoid sinuses and the ethmoid air cells.there is nasal septal deviation to the left with a bony spur.the bony septum of the sphenoid sinus inserts on the right superiorly, subjacent to the right carotid groove.there are no masses identified within the paranasal sinuses.the osteomeatal units are patent bilaterally.no blastic or lytic bony lesions are seen.the visualized portions of the brain parenchyma appear within normal limits.

text: the maxillary sinuses bilaterally are clear.frontal sinus is clear.there is bilateral ethmoid sinus opacification and an air fluid level seen in the left sphenoid sinus.in addition, there is fluid in both mastoid air cells and the middle ear cavities.these findings are new from the visualized sinuses seen in the head ct dated ___.the osseous structures demonstrate no destructive changes.the clinoids are not aerated.the sphenoid septum attaches at the right carotid siphon.

text: there is a small amount of opacification of the posterior aspect of the left sphenoid sinus and portions of the right sphenoid sinus may represent mucosal thickening versus a small amount of fluid.there is a nasogastric tube in place which is coiled but is incompletely visualized.the maxillary sinuses and frontal sinuses are unremarkable.the visualized orbits are within normal limits.there is opacification of both mastoids.
summary: minimal disease involving the sphenoid sinus.mastoid thickening.there is no evidence of osseous erosions.it should be noted that it can be seen in cases in which nasogastric tubes have been placed.

text: again noted are areas of high attenuation in the left frontal lobe in intraparenchymal and subarachnoid location.these are stable in appearance.there is no significant mass effect associated.there is no shift of midline structures.again seen are fractures of the anterior wall of the maxillary sinus extending in the proximal aspect of the lacrimal canal and into the inferior orbital wall.there are fractures of the nasal bone and the nasal septum.fluid is identified in the left mastoid cells.

text: there has been interval increase in degree of polysinus disease.there is mucosal thickening and/or fluid in bilateral maxillary sinuses, right greater than left, sphenoid and ethmoid sinus, and to a lesser extent frontal sinuses.the nasal septum is midline, and the sphenoid septum inserts on the right carotid groove.the laminae papyracea are intact bilaterally.the cribriform plates are symmetrically positioned and intact.

text: there is hematoma in the right periorbital region and at the base of the nose.there is no fracture.mucosal thickening is noted in the ethmoid and maxillary sinuses and frontal sinuses..in the upper cervical spine, there is no fracture or spondylolisthesis.

text: the degree of pneumocephalus has decreased in the interval.though this study is not optimized for visualizing brain, there is persistent left frontal contusion with surrounding edema in the region of the surgical intervention and trauma.surgical mesh exterior to the left frontal fracture and orbital rim fracture is evident.surgical mesh is also seen superior to the left orbital roof.the osseous fragments in this region appear near anatomic alignment.no orbital gas is seen.there does appear to be some discontinuity of the left orbital floor on reconstructed images; however, these reconstructions are somewhat limited by stair step artifact.there are again noted fractures of the lateral and anterior walls of bilateral maxillary sinuses with persistent heterogeneous high density material in the maxillary sinuses consistent with hemorrhage.the muscles of the left orbit or the orbital fat do not appear entrapped in any of the described fractures

text: no mucosal thickening is seen in any of the paranasal sinuses.the patient is asymmetrically positioned in the scanner.on the right in the subcutaneous tissues adjacent to the alveolar ridge of the maxilla there is soft tissue density following the contour of the bone.this region is incompletely imaged on the left and so symmetry cannot be fully assessed.correlation with clinical exam is recommended.the osseous structures are unremarkable.

text: the patient is s/p left temporal craniotomy.eeg leads are in place.there is thickening of the skull.has the patient received long-term dilantin therapy? there is a probable retention cyst within the left frontal sinus.the remainder of the paranasal sinuses appear to be clear.no obvious brain abnormalities are appreciated although this is not a sensitive test for brain pathology.

text: the frontal, maxillary, ethmoid and sphenoid sinuses are normal.the orbits appear normal.the maxilla is normal.note is made of posterior displacement of the four anterior mandibular teeth.there is minor discontinuity of the superior anterior cortex of the mandible.more inferiorly, the mandible appears intact.there is no evidence of malialignment.the temporotemporal mandibular joint is not included in this series.

text: the patient is s/p interval bilateral antrostomies and ethmoidectomies.there is moderate mucosal thickening involving the right maxillary sinus.this is not significantly changed compared with the prior study.there is a new small air fluid level within the left maxillary sinus.there is minimal mucosal thickening involving the ethmoid sinus.there is moderate mucosal thickening involving the sphenoid sinus.this is new compared with the prior study.the nasal septum is midline.the frontal sinuses are clear.the mastoid air cells are incompletely visualized on this study.however, there is mild opacification of the mastoid air cells bilaterally.no osseous destruction is identified.

text: there is essentially complete opacification of the right maxillary sinus.a 9 mm x 3 mm radiopaque foreign body is present and obstructing the right ostiomeatal outlet.this object probably arrived in this location through a defect in the right maxillary superior alveolar ridge, where a tooth extraction had been performed.there is minimal dependent left maxillary mucosal thickening.there is deviation of the nasal septum to the left with impingement of the left inferior nasal turbinate.the left ostiomeatal unit is widely patent.the ethmoid and sphenoid sinuses are well aerated.there is a multipartite sphenoid septum with insertions in the midline and along the right carotid groove.the anterior clinoids are not pneumatized and the cribriform plates are equal heights and symmetric.

text: multiple fractures are identified in the right temporal bone and are seen to be extending anteriorly into the lateral wall of the right orbit and across the orbital roof and through the laminae paprycea into the right ethmoid sinus.while there is displacement of the fracture fragments in the lateral temporal bone, the fractures along the orbits and ethmoid sinus are nondisplaced.there is no entrapment of fat or extraocular muscle.air-fluid levels are noted in the ethmoid and right maxillary sinuses and there is opacification within the sphenoid sinus, which does not demonstrate a clear air-fluid level.there is a fracture of the right occipital bone, which can be seen extending to the right anterior portion of the foramen magnum.there is no appreciable displacement along the fracture plane.the visualized portions of c1 and c2 demonstrate no fractures.there is no evidence of impingement on the spinal cord as it exits the foramen magnum.subdural blood is noted anterior to the frontal lobes bilaterally, right greater than left, and there are two air bubbles within this fluid collection on the right.in addition, there appears to be interval slight increase in the right-sided subdural hemorrhage laterally.
summary: fractures extending from the temporal bone into the lateral, superior and medial aspects of the right orbit with no evidence of displacement or entrapment of these periorbital fractures.fracture of the right occipital bone extending to the basilar occiput and terminating at the foramen magnum, as described above.interval increase in subdural hematoma since the prior ct study approximately 30 minutes ago.a follow-up ct of the head is recommended to evluate progression.the above findings were discussed by phone with the referring physician, ___.___ ___ at approximately 4:55 pm on ___.

text: an ng tube and nasal o2 prongs are in place.there is minimal mucosal thickening of the maxillary sinuses.the sinuses are otherwise clear.no bony abnormalities are appreciated.

text: as on the patient's prior examinations, there is high density material identified within the right maxillary sinus consistent with hemorrhage.there is a tiny nondisplaced fracture through the floor of the right orbit.a second tiny fracture is identified within the lamina papyracea.this second small fracture is also not significantly displaced.fluid remains present in the left maxillary sinus in addition to the ethmoid sinuses with a small amount of mucosal thickening in the right sphenoid sinus.no other fractures are identified.there is no evidence of herniation of fat or other orbital contents through the small fracture regions.the globes are normal in appearance.

text: again there are mildly displaced fractures of both the right and left nasal bones.no other fractures are identified.there is soft-tissue density within the ethmoid, sphenoid, and maxillary sinuses, likely due to retained secretions or blood products.there is also soft-tissue density within the nasopharynx.the patient has an endotracheal tube, whose presence may contribute to the sinus findings noted above.the soft tissues are symmetric.the orbits, including orbital floor and laminae papyracea appear normal.the limited evaluation of the base of the brain is unremarkable.coronal reconstructions support the above findings.

text: there is persistent mucosal thickening of the right maxillary sinus however there has been improvement compared to the prior exam.previously there was near complete opacification of the right maxillary sinus.the patient is status post surgery to the right maxillary sinus medial wall and the previous opacity felt to represent an osteoma is no longer seen.there is mucosal thickening and near complete obliteration of the new, enlarged ostomy to the right maxillary sinus.there is also mucosal thickening involving the right ethmoid air cells.the nasal septum deviates to the left and there is a small left nasal spur.there has been interval removal of the bone fragment from the right medial maxillary sinus wall.there is also a minimal amount of mucosal thickening of the right frontal sinus.the ethmoidal and frontal sinus thickening were not present on the prior study.the remainder of the anatomic survey is unchanged.

text: there is a tripod fracture identified on the left involving the inferior and lateral orbital walls and the zygomatic process of the maxillary bone.it is comminuted at its apex.there is intraorbital gas.there is no retrobulbar hemorrhage.there is no appreciable proptosis.there is opacification of the left maxillary sinus.the lamina papyracea on the left appears to be discontinuous and shattered.the orbital roof appears intact.fracture also appears to involve the pterygoid plate on the left.there is a comminuted nasal bone fracture as well.an osseous fragment from the comminuted fracture of the lateral wall of the orbit on the left is protruding somewhat into the orbit.there does not appear to be herniation of extraocular muscles, though the globe appears slightly displaced downward and to the left, in the direction of the fracture.there is a fracture of the anterior aspect of the temporal glenoid fossa on the left.

text: on axial images, there is an air fluid level filling half of the right maxillary sinus, as well as mild mucosal thickening on the left.the frontal, ethmoid, sphenoid, and mastid sinuses are aerated.there are no fractures of sinuses or of the nasal bones.the orbits and frontal bones are intact.there is a comminuted fracture of the right mandibular ramus, as well as a fracture at the left body of the mandible, both of which are surrounded by punctate air collections, consistent with soft tissue injury.the temporomandibular joint appears intact, with the condyle centered within the fossa.limited views of the brain, after contrast administration for a separate study, demonstrate a new intraparenchymal hemorrhage in the white matter adjacent to the tip of the right frontal ___ and in the splenium of the corpus callosum.there is also development of parenchymal hemorrhage within the right anterior temporal lobe and left inferior frontal lobe.there also appears to be the development of a left frontal small subdural hemorrhage or extraaxial collection.there is no major shift of structures appreciated on limited views.the patient is intubated with ___ ___-orogastric tube in place.

text: the frontal sinuses are clear.there is mucosal thickening along the lateral border of the right maxillary sinus.the left maxillary sinus is clear.the infundibulae of the osteomeatal complexes are clear.there is minimal mucosal thickening present within the ethmoid air cells bilaterally as well as in the left side of the sphenoid sinuses.the sphenoid septum inserts onto the left carotid groove.there is no aeration of the clinoid processes.the cribriform plates are level bilaterally.the septum papyracea is intact bilaterally.the nasal cavity and nasal septum are unremarkable.there is no fluid present, and no air fluid levels present within any of the paranasal sinuses.the middle ear cavities and visualized portions of the mastoid air cells are filled with fluid bilaterally.

text: multiple orbital fractures are identified extending through the frontal bone and the orbital floor, the right temporal bone.there is also fracture of the lamina papyracea, with compression of the ethmoid air cells.there are fractures of the lateral and anterior wall of the right maxillary sinus.there is fracture of the zygomatic arch.the coronal images demonstrate a fracture of the floor of the orbit.there is a small amount of fat which herniates through the fracture fragments.the muscle does not (although a clinical diagnosis).there is a large mucocele within the left maxillary sinus.there is mucosal thickening involving the right maxillary sinus.there is complete opacification of the sphenoid sinus.there is inferior displacement of the roof of the right orbit which involves the right cribriform plate which is depressed inferiorly 3-4 mm.there is significant narrowing of the right ostiomeatal complex.the visualized aspect of the brain again demonstrates the encephalomalacic changes in the right frontal lobe.there is no evidence of hemorrhage.

text: there are air-fluid levels in bilateral maxillary sinuses and extensive soft-tissue density material within bilateral ethoidal air cells.there is almost complete opacification of bilateral frontal sinuses and air-fluid levels in bilateral sphenoid sinuses, especially on the left.there are no bone erosions.the visualized portions of the brain are unremarkable.there has been interval significant worsening in the amount of sinus disease.

text: there is mucosal thickening of the right frontal sinus and bilateral maxillary sinuses, right greater than left.there is extensive soft tissue density material within the right ethmoidal air cells and air fluid levels in the sphenoid sinuses.there is opacification of bilateral mastoid air cells.the anterior clinoids are not aerated.the lamina papyracea are intact.there is a tiny left nasal spur.the cribriform plates are symmetric.the patient has an ng tube.there is a metallic plate at the vertex of the skull.
