text: there are bilateral, near complete opacification of the frontal sinuses with air fluid levels.there is mucosal thickening with some possible air fluid levels within the ethmoid air cells bilaterally.air fluid levels are present in both maxillary sinuses, and the infundibulae of the ostiomeatal complexes are blocked bilaterally.there is an air fluid level within the sphenoid sinus, predominantly on the left.there is a bipartite sphenoid sinus septum.there is no aeration of the anterior clinoid processes bilaterally.the cribriform plates are level.the nasal septum deviates to the right anteriorly.the lamina papyracea is intact bilaterally.the overall appearance of the patient's sinusitis is unchanged compared to the prior study.
summary: pan sinusitis, unchanged from ___.the patient was in the vti headset for stereotactic localization purposes.

text: a comminuted fracture of the nasal bones is noted with mild rightward deflection.an air fluid level is noted in the left maxillary sinus, but no other fractures are seen.polypoid mucosal thickening is noted in the right frontal sinus.mild mucosal thickening is noted in the ethmoid sinuses.the soft tissues of the pharynx are unremarkable.
summary: comminuted nasal bone fracture with rightward deviation.air fluid level in the left maxillary sinus with no additional fractures.

text: extensive facial bone fractures are noted involving the nasal bones, the nasal septum, the maxillary bones bilaterally, as well as the posterior right zygoma.orbital air is noted bilaterally indicating fracture into the orbits.there is fracture of both lamina papyracea, the orbital floors, the right lateral orbital wall and probably the left fovea ethmoidalis.orbital contents are grossly normal and there is no herniation of orbital contents.extensive opacification with air fluid levels is noted in the maxillary, ethmoid, and frontal sinuses.a small amount of fluid is also noted dependently in the sphenoid sinus.a skull base fracture is not seen.there is an old crabiotomy defect in the right temporal bone also.a nasogastric tube and endotracheal tube have been placed.the pharynx is nearly completely opacified with several fluid levels which may represent blood and edema.
summary: extensive facial bone fractures as described above.some of the fractures, especially the orbital floor fractures, would be better visualized with direct coronal scans.this may be considered when the patient is able to position for them.there would also be improved visualization of the floor of the anterior cranial fossa/cribriform plates.

text: there is a comminuted fracture of the ramus of the right mandible with significant overlap of the fracture fragments by approximately 1 cm.additionally, there is a nondisplaced fracture through the anterior portion of the mandible on the left.the temporomandibular joints appear intact, although there is widening of the right temporomandibular joint in comparison with the left.there are several comminuted fractures involving the lateral wall of the right maxillary sinus with high attenuation material within the sinus consistent with hemorrhage.fracture also extends through the anterior portion of the sinus along the inferior portion of the right orbit.this fracture through the floor of the right orbit is not significantly displaced and there is no evidence of herniation of the orbital contents through this fracture.there is also a fracture involving the lateral wall of the orbit posteriorly.there is an air-fluid level in the left maxillary sinus and there is the question of a slight interruption of the medial wall of the left maxillary sinus.the left orbit appears intact.there is soft tissue density in the right sphenoid sinus but this appears rounded rather than as an air- fluid level.again, no fracture at the site of the patient's scalp laceration is identified.
summary: fracture of the floor of the right orbit without significant displacement of the fracture fragments or evidence of herniation of the orbital contents.fracture also involves the lateral wall of the right orbit.fractures involving the right mandibular ramus and left mandible anteriorly.comminuted fractures of the right maxillary sinus laterally and anteriorly.possible small nondisplaced fracture of the left maxillary sinus.

text: again noted are multiple facial fractures, which remain unchanged from the prior exam.there is slight worsening of mucosal thickening in all the paranasal sinuses when compared to the prior study, associated with air fluid levels.the previously noted subdural gas is not well visualized on the prior study.
summary: there is overall worsening of diffuse brain edema, with worsening of shift of normally midline structures.there is evidence of a left pca stroke.there is interval resolution of previously noted left-sided subdural gas.worsening of diffuse mucosal disease in the paranasal sinuses.

text: there is a fracture through the portion of the left side of the hyoid bone with associated soft tissue swelling posteromedial to this which is creating a small amount of mass effect on the airway.there is a multi________ fracture of the left anterior portion of the mandible.anterior and lateral to this in the soft tissues there is a moderate degree of soft tissue swelling with multiple hyperintense fragments of debris.the lamina papyracea and floor of the orbits appear to be intact bilaterally.there is no sign of fluid in the paranasal sinuses.
summary: fractures of the mandible and hyoid bone as described above.soft tissue swelling in the left paratracheal region.

text: there are air-fluid levels present in the left maxillary, bilateral sphenoid and frontal sinuses, as well as the majority of the ethmoid air cells.no bone destruction is identified.there is mucosal thickening in the right maxillary sinus.the orbits are unremarkable.the patient is intubated and there is an ng tube present.
summary: air-fluid levels throughout the paranasal sinuses in this intubated patient.the presence of fluid is not unexpected given the intubated status and it is not possible to ascertain whether this fluid is sterile or infected on ct imaging.

text: the left frontal air cell is not as severely opacified, compared to the prior study.there is mucosal thickening of the left maxillary sinus with an air fluid level.in the right maxillary sinus there is a retention cyst vs.polyp measuring 7 mm.mild mucosal thickening of the left ethmoidal air cells.the sphenoid sinuses are clear.compared to the prior study of ___, there appears to be some improvement in the patient's sinusitis.the nasal septum is midline and the cribriform plates are symmetric and equal in height.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.the visualized brain shows multiple areas of decreased attenuation within the white matter in the frontal lobes bilaterally, unchanged in appearance from the prior examination.
summary: air fluid level with mucosal thickening in the left maxillary sinus, which could indicate acute inflammatory process.right maxillary sinus mucous retention cyst.mild mucosal thickening of the left frontal air cell and left ethmoidal air cells.overall, the level of sinusitis appears slightly improved compared to the prior study.

text: there is abundant fluid and mucosal thickening with near total opacification of all the paranasal sinuses.the nasal septum is deviated to the right.a complete fracture of the head of the mandibular condyle on the left is identified with anterior medial displacement of the bone fragment.other facial fractures are not identified, and the walls of the orbits and maxillae are intact.please note that the mandible is incompletely scanned to its most caudal extension.the lamina papyrcea are intact and the cribiform plates are symmetrical in height.there is a septum within the sphenoid sinus which is midline.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.
summary: pan sinusitis.left complete fracture dislocation of the head of the mandibular condyle.

text: there are extensive comminuted fractures of the mid facial bones.specifically, there are displaced fractures of anterior and medial walls of bilateral maxillary sinuses, nasal septum, multiple ethmoid septa, bilateral lamina papyracea, and nasal bones.there is a fracture of the left frontal sinus with a more than 1 cm stepoff, extending into the left frontal bone and left zygomatic arch.non-displaced fracture of the basisphenoid bone is also seen.bubbles of gas are seen within both orbits and above the left orbital roof.soft tissues within the orbits appear intact.there is partial opacification of most of the sinuses secondary to extensive fractures.sagittal and coronal reconstruction images show extensive comminuted and displaced fractures of the mid facial bones.
summary: extensive mid face fractures with intracranial gas and more than 1 cm stepoff involving the left frontal sinus.

text: there are globular appearing soft tissue densities within the inferior maxillary sinuses, worse on the left than the right.no air-fluid levels are present.there is mild mucosal thickening of the sphenoid sinus, as well as the ethmoid air cells.the frontal sinuses are clear.a ng tube is present within the left nostril.the ostiomeatal unit of the left appears mildly narrowed by mucosal thickening.the ostiomeatal unit on the right appears patent.there is deviation of the nasal septum to the right.the anterior clinoids are not pneumatized.the sphenoid septum is multipartite with insertion on the right carotid groove.visualized portions of the mastoids anf middle ear cavities are clear.
summary: mild amount of mucosal thickening within the ethmoid air cells, nasal cavity and sphenoid sinus.globular density within the inferior maxillary sinuses, which could represent focal mucosal thickening, retention cysts or polyps.

text: the frontal bones are intact.no fractures of the skull base or sphenoid are identified.the mastoids are not completely in view, but the middle ear cavities are aerated.there is a depressed fracture of the posterolateral wall of the left maxillary sinus, which does not appear to involve the orbital floor.there is herniation of infratemporal fat through the fracture, into the maxillary sinus.bone fragments are also internally displaced.there is a shallower depressed fracture of the right posterolateral maxillary sinus wall.there are bone fragments and fat displaced into the right sinus cavity, as well.the right orbital floor also appears to be intact.there is opacification of a few of the posterior left ethmoid air cells.an acute lamina papyracea fracture is not clearly delineated.the nasal bones are intact.there are no fractures of the zygomatic arches.the body of the maxilla is also intact.there is a fracture through the body of the mandible, left of midline.fracture fragments are not displaced.the temporo-mandibular joints are normally aligned.there is fluid in the sphenoid sinus and the maxillary sinuses.
summary: there are depressed maxillary sinus fractures with the left fracture fragments further displaced into the maxillary sinus than the right.there is also a fracture of the mandible.there are no fractures of the skull base or sphenoid identified and the orbits appear to be intact.

text: there is opacification of the sphenoid air cells, likely by a mixture of fluid and mucosal thickening.the ethmoid, maxillary and frontal sinuses are clear.there is a non-displaced fracture of the left coronoid process of the mandible.even in retrospect, this fracture is virtually invisible on the ___ study- perhaps interval demineralization has increased the visiblity of the fracture.the temporomandibular joints are intact and in normal position.there is soft tissue opacification of the mastoid air cells on the left and a longitudinal fracture is again seen through the mastoid portion of the left temporal bone in this region.there is near complete clearance of soft tissue density from within the left middle ear canal and currently only a small amount of soft tissue thickening is seen within the left external auditory canal.no gas is seen within the soft tissue planes of the neck.there are no asymmetric soft tissue densities.the orbital walls are intact.
summary: redemonstration of left temporal bone fracture as described above.left mandibular coronoid process fracture, which even in retrospect, is virtually invisible on prior ct scans.intact tmjs bilaterally.

text: there is near total opacification of the frontal air cells, maxillary, ethmoidal and sphenoid sinuses.there is significant opacification of the mastoid air cells bilaterally.these findings could all be secondary to the patient's intubated state, and cannot be distinguished from acute sinusitis.the visualized portions of the brain show no hemorrhage, mass effect, or shift of normally midline structures, though the study is not optimized for brain imaging.
summary: significant opacification of the sinuses and mastoid cells as described above.this could be related to the patient's intubation; however, acute sinusitis cannot be ruled out.

text: again noted are multiple fractures at the base of the skull in the region of the paranasal sinuses.again noted are fractures through the left mandible, left zygomatic arch, right and left lateral maxillary antral walls.also noted are multiple fractures present involving the anterior and the lateral walls of the sphenoid sinuses, temporal and occpital bones.there are also fractures of the left medial and the lateral pterygoid process.a fracture is seen extending though left anterior clinoid process.air fluid level is noted in the frontal sinuses bilaterally and the maxillary sinuses bilaterally.there is near opacification of the sphenoidal sinuses and the ethmoidal air cells.the anterior sphenoid processes are not pneumatized.patient is intubated, with a nasogastric tube and endotracheal tube noted.
summary: there is stable appearance of multiple fractures involving the paranasal sinuses and the skull base, in the region of the medial sphenoid, temporal, and occipital bones.no significant change from the prior study obtained on ___.please refer to the ct of the head on ___ for detailed description of the brain.

text: as described previously, there are comminuted fractures extending through the superior, lateral and inferior margins of both orbits.a metal plate has been placed along the roof of the right orbit.the majority of the paranasal sinuses are opacified with high attenuation material.a tiny osseous fragment is seen posterolateral and superior to the left globe, adjacent to soft tissue density which extends into the orbit and displaces the superior rectus inferiorly.the overall appearance is unchanged from the prior study, including the presence of several depressed bone fragments along the superior portions of the mid-orbits.since the prior study, a fragment of sphenoid bone along the lateral border of the posterior left orbit has become minimally displaced.this fragment is adjacent to the optic nerve and is a component of the distal portion of the optic canal.moderate left proptosis is unchanged.hemorrhagic material is seen within the left frontal lobe.
summary: slight displacement of a fracture fragment which forms part of the lateral wall of the distal optic canal on the left.this finding could explain recent development of a left afferent defect on clinical exam.

text: there are fluid levels in almost completely opacified sphenoid air cells, and in the posterior ethmoid sinuses.there are also some opacified anterior ethmoid air cells and there is fluid in the frontal sinuses, especially on the left.mucosal thickening and fluid is present in both maxillary sinuses.the left osteomeatal complex appears aerated.the right osteomeatal unit is more difficult to see on the reformatted images.the nasal cavity is normal and septum is roughly midline.there is limited visualization of the maxilla due to the patient's position in the scanner.there is no frank bone destruction.fluid is present in the middle ear cavities bilaterally and in portions of the mastoid air cells visualized.
summary: there is extensive acute sinusitis.there may be mastoiditis and otitis media as well.clinical correlation is recommended.

text: there is a transverse fracture through the neck of the left condyloid process of the mandible.there is mild displacement of the proximal fracture fragment laterally.the condyle is slightly medially subluxed within the condyloid fossa.there is a tiny fracture fragment at the fracture site.the remainder of the mandible appears normal.there is no fluid within the maxillary, ethmoid or sphenoid sinuses.the frontal sinuses are hypoplastic.the zygomatic bones are normal.the orbits are unremarkable.
summary: fracture of the neck of the left condyloid process.there is slight medial subluxation of the condyle within the temporomandibular joint space.

text: there is a fracture through the right angle of the mandible extending into the posterior most molar.additionally there is a vertical fracture through the anterior mandible (mental portion).the coronoid and condylar processes are within normal limits.no other fractures are seen.the sphenoid sinus is free of air-fluid levels.there is a mild amount of fluid dependently within the right maxillary sinus and mucosal thickening of the ethmoid air cells which could be related to patient's immobility.no fractures are seen through the maxillary sinus.the left anterior clinoid is pneumatized.there is a nasal spur deviating the nasal septum to the right.there is soft tissue swelling around the fracture as expected.there is a small amount of subcutaneous gas adjacent to the right mandibular fracture.the visualized portion of the upper cervical spine is within normal limits.
summary: mandibular fractures through the right angle of the mandible and through the mental process.questionable fracture/ diastasis through the hardpalate (arrows)

text: there is evidence of previous uncinectomy in medial maxillary and ethmoid surgery.the frontal sinuses are clear.there is thickening of the ethmoid cells.there is mild thickening of the maxillary sinuses.there is mild thickening also of the sphenoid sinus.the left cribriform plate is 2 mm higher than the right.the anterior clinoids are not pneumatized.the sphenoid septum inserts on the right carotid sulcus.
summary: mild membrane thickening in multiple sinuses, as described.

text: there is no evidence of facial bone fractures.the paranasal sinuses are clear.there is subcutaneous air in the right periorbital region which does not extend into the orbit.the globe and orbits appear normal.note is made of bilateral ___ bullosa.
summary: no facial bone fractures.

text: there is a comminuted fracture through the frontal sinus with depression into the frontal sinus and minimal amount of depression of the inner table anterior to the frontal lobes.additionally, there are fractures through bilateral laminae papyraceae, i.e.the medial orbital wall; although the cribriform plate cannot be evaluated well by ct, given the adjacent fractures, a cribriform plate fracture is suspected.there is no intracranial gas.there is blood within the frontal sinuses, ethmoid air cells and maxillary sinuses.the coronal reformatted images support the above findings and demonstrate air within both retrobulbar spaces.the upper cervical spine is within normal limits.
summary: depressed fracture through the frontal bone extending intracranially, frontal sinus, fractures through both medial orbital walls.clinical correlation for possible cribriform plate fracture.fracture of the anterior wall of right maxillary sinus and possible fracture of the lateral wall of left maxillary sinus.

text: there is fluid in the sphenoid sinuses bilaterally, the sphenoid septum inserts into the left carotid groove.there is bilateral mucosal thickening and air fluid level in the maxillary sinuses.there is fluid in the ethmoid sinuses as well.there is mucosal thickening of the right frontal sinus as well.the visualized mastoid air cells are clear.
summary: extensive sinustitis of the maxillary, ethmoidal, sphenoid and frontal sinuses.mri with contrastis a moresensitive study to exclude intracranial extension.

text: since the examination there has been surgery on the medial aspect of the right maxillary sinus.the post surgical changes around the left maxillary sinus are again identified.there is increased soft tissue thickening in the inferior aspect of the left maxillary sinus when compared to the previous examination.the soft tissue thickening in the right maxillary sinus is essentially similar to the prior study.the frontal sinuses are clear.the ethmoid sinuses demonstrates only minimal thickening.the sphenoid sinuses are clear.there is aeration of both anterior clinoids.sphenoid septum inserts on the right carotid sulcus.
summary: some increased soft tissue thickening inferior aspect of left maxillary sinus compared to previous examination.intervening surgery on right maxillary sinus as described.

text: multiple fractures are again identified.these include fractures of the left lateral orbital wall, left orbital floor and left zygomatic arch.comminuted fractures of the left anterior and lateral maxillary sinus walls area also noted.there is a small fracture of the right lateral orbital wall.the right inferior orbital wall is intact.there is a small amount of right orbital emphysema adjacent to the right lamina papyracea.fluid is present within both maxillary sinuses.no evidence of ocular muscle entrapment.again demonstrated is a markedly comminuted fracture of the right mandiblular ramus.there is a fracture of the left mandible as well.there is extensive soft tissue emphysema.there is a small oblique fracture through the left pterygoid plate region.there is minimal mucosal thickening in the sphenoid sinus.the frontal sinuses are hypoplastic.the patient is intubated and a ng tube is present.
summary: multiple facial fractures as noted above.bilateral mandibular rami fractures.the only new fracture detected is of the left pterygoid plate region.this is nondisplaced.no fluid is present within the mastoid sinuses, which are not entirely visualized on this examination.

text: there is a comminuted fracture of the superior aspect of the right mandibular ramus.the condyle is not fractured.there is inferiomedial displacement of the mandibular condyle within the temporomandibular joint.there is medial angulation of the condyle.no other mandibular fractures are identified.there is moderate soft tissue swelling surrouding the right mandibular ramus.the mastoids are pneumatized.the sphenoid, ethmoid, frontal and maxillary sinuses are clear.
summary: there is a fracture of the superior portion of the right mandibular ramus.there is associated angulation of the condyle medially.the fracture does not extend into the joint space.these findings were directly communicated to dr.___ at 5:00 pm on ___, ___.

text: there is evidence of mucosal thickening and fluid levels within the bilateral maxillary sinuses, ethmoid air cells, and sphenoid sinuses bilaterally.the nasal septum is midline and there is no evidence of spur.the lamina papyracea are intact.the cribriform plates are symmetric in height.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.there is a septum in the sphenoid sinus which inserts on the left carotid groove.please note that the patient is intubated.
summary: mucosal thickening and air-fluid levels throughout the maxillary sinuses, ethmoid air cells, and sphenoid sinuses bilaterally.please note that the patient is intubated which may account for the findings.anatomy as described above.

text: the visualized maxillary sinuses are clear.there is marked dental artifact obscuring the alveolar ridges; within this significant limitation, the views of the mandible demonstrate no gross evidence of bone destruction.the visualized submandibular and parotid glands are symmetric and demonstrate no overt abnormalities on this non- contrast examination.the airway is patent throughout.the soft tissues of the nasopharynx and oropharynx are symmetric.there is no perceptible evidence of abscess.
summary: no overt evidence of abscess.however, this study is quite insensitive in the detection of early osteomyelitis, and virtually insensitive in detecting dental infections.correlative bone scan needs to be considered if osseous infection is suspected, as well a maxillofacial consultation.

text: there is no sign of mucosal thickening involving either the frontal, ethmoid, or left maxillary sinus.there is an 8 mm mucous retention cyst at the inferior portion of the left maxillary sinus.additionally, there is moderate mucosal thickening involving the right sphenoid sinus air cell.there is a lateral septation of the right maxillary sinus.the left anterior clinoid process is pneumatized, while the right is not.the sphenoid septum is multipartite, with an insertion at the left carotid groove.the nasal septum deviates towards the left.the ostiomeatal complexes are patent.the left cribriform plate is 2 mm superior to the right.note is made of phthisis bulbi of the right globe; there is a retinal band around the left.note is also made of bilaterally calcified distal vertebral arteries and moderate atrophy of the brain.
summary: moderate mucosal thickening involving the right sphenoid sinus air cell with a mucus retention cyst in the left maxillary sinus.no evidence of acute sinusitus.prominent atherosclerotic disease involving the vertebral arteries.moderate brain atrophy.

text: fractures are seen in the subcondylar regions of both vertical mandibular rami.on the left, there is no apparent subluxation of the mandibular condyle from the ususal temporomandibular joint alignment.the subcondylar fracture is comminuted and the inferior ramus fragment is displaced medially by less than the width of the bone and foreshortened by approximately 1 cm.on the right, the mandibular condyle is dislocated inferiorly, anteriorly, and medially from the temporal fossa.when viewed from the coronal orientation, the condyle is rotated medially.the infracondylar fracture is comminuted and the fracture fragments are impacted.multiple facial fractures are again identified.the lateral wall of the maxillary sinus is impacted medially.fracture is again seen through the left lateral pterygoid plate.there is fracture of the left orbital floor without herniation of intraorbital contents and there is fracture of the lateral wall of the left orbit.a buckle fracture is seen within the middle aspect of the left zygomatic arch.a small amount of circumferential mucosal thickening is seen within the left maxillary sinus, but there is near-complete interval resolution of mucosal thickening and fluid level seen throughout most of the paranasal sinuses on the prior examination.there has been interval extubation and interval removal of an ng tube.radiopaque foreign bodies are seen in the subcutaneous soft tissues lateral and superior to the left orbit.
summary: alignment of mandibular fracture as described above.radiopaque foreign bodies are seen lateral and superior to the left orbit.these were present on the prior examination.

text: no fractures are seen.the imaged paranasal sinuses are intact without air fluiud levels.the lamina papyracea are intact and the cribriform plates are of equal height.no intraorbital emphysema is seen.the nasal septum is midline.
summary: fluid noted in the right mastoid air cells with fluid in the right middle and external ear, raising the possibility of subtle right mastoid fracture.fluid/hematoma noted in the left external ear.

text: there are aerosolized secretions within the sphenoid sinus.there is also soft-tissue opacity within the maxillary sinuses bilaterally as well as within the ethmoid sinuses, to a lesser extent.there are also aerosolized secretions in the right frontal sinus.these findings could be secondary to the patient's intubated status.the cribriform plates are symmetric.the lamina papyracea is intact.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.the visualized soft-tissue structures are otherwise unremarkable.
summary: soft-tissue opacification of the paranasal sinuses, as described.this is a nonspecific appearance.in a patient who is intubated, this may be secondary to the patient's intubation status.

text: mild to moderate mucosal thickening is noted in both maxillary sinuses.the left ostiomeatal unit appears obstructed by the thickened mucosa.the right ostiomeatal unit appears patent.there is no air-fluid level.the frontal and sphenoid sinuses appear clear.mild mucosal thickening is also noted in the ethmoid air cells.the laminae papyracea and cribriform plates are intact and symmetric.there is no pneumatization of the anterior clinoid processes.the sphenoid sinus septum is midline.there is no nasal septal deviation.a small right-sided spur is noted arising from the nasal septum.
summary: mucosal thickening of the paranasal sinuses with obstruction of the left ostiomeatal unit.no air-fluid levels.

text: there is near-complete opacification of the right maxillary sinus.there is opacification of the multiple ethmoid air cells.mucosal thickening is present in both frontal, sphenoid, in the left maxillary sinus, as well as the remaining unopacified ethmoid air cells.mucosal thickening is also present about the nasal turbinates.both infundibula of the ostiomeatal complexes are blocked.there is a partially opacified left middle ___ bullosa.there is aeration of both anterior clinoid processes.the main sphenoid septum inserts on the midline.the lamina papyracea is intact bilaterally.there is minimal rightward septal deviation.the cribriform plates are level.
summary: near-complete opacification of the right maxillary sinus.complete opacification of numerous ethmoid air cells.mucosal thickening throughout the remaining paranasal sinuses and nasal cavity.these results were discussed with ___ ___, a member of the medical house staff, at the time of interpretation.

text: there is no fracture seen within the mandible.both tmj's are intact.there is no subluxation or dislocation.there is no fracture of the pterygoid plates.no asymmetric soft tissue densities are seen within the oropharynx.
summary: no jaw fracture.

text: evaluation of the paranasal sinuses reveals minimal mucosal thickening in the sphenoid air cells bilaterally, with no air-fluid levels seen.a small soft-tissue polyp is seen in the left maxillary sinus.otherwise, the rest of the paranasal sinuses are well aerated without air- fluid levels.evaluation following the administration of iv contrast reveals no focal wall enhancing fluid collections representing abscess.the soft tissues of the oropharynx, nasopharynx and upper hypopharynx are symmetrical and normal.the vascular structures are normal and symmetrical.no lymph node enlargement is seen.the bones show no fractures or suspicious lytic and/or sclerotic lesions.the base of the brain is unremarkable.evaluation of the temporomandibular joints reveals no adjacent inflammatory change and/or fluid collections.
summary: no abscess or sinusitis.mri with contrast is a more sensitive exam and may be performed if clinically warranted.

text: an endotracheal tube is in place.there is increased opacification within the ethmoid and sphenoid sinuses.there is also mild mucosal thickening of the maxillary sinuses, slightly greater on the right than on the left.no frontal sinuses are present.the osseous structures are unremarkale.no soft tissues abnormalities are identified.
summary: increased opacification of the paranasal sinuses, as described.infection cannot be excluded.

text: there is a fracture of the right superior orbital bone extending superiorly.in addition, there is a fracture of the right medial orbital bone seen on series 2, image 50.there are at least 2 fractures of the left anterior wall and a fracture of the alteral wall of the left maxillary sinus with slight inward displacement seen on series 2, image 19.possible fracture of the anterior wall of the right maxillary sinus.fracture of the sphenoid septum.basal skull fracture cannot be excluded.there are air fluid levels present bilaterally in the frontal sinuses.in addition, there is an air fluid level in the right maxillary sinus and left maxillary sinus is completely filled with increased density consistent with hemorrhage.the ethmoid sinuses are fluid filled as well, right greater than left.there is an air fluid level in the left sphenoid sinus with opacification of the right sphenoid sinus.the mastoid air cells are intact.soft tissue windows show no pre-orbital hemorrhage.extra occular muscles appear intact.
summary: fractures of the both maxillary sinuses, right medial and superior orbital bones.spehoid septum frcture and possible fracture of the skull base.

text: there is a comminuted fracture through both frontal sinuses with involvement of the inner table and a depressed fragment.aerosolized fluid is present in the sinuses.the nasal bones are fractured as well as both laminae papyracea.layering of aerosolized fluid is present within the ethmoid air cells.in addition, there is a fracture of the right and left orbital roofs as well as the superior aspects of both maxillary sinuses.
summary: extensive facial fractures as described above.2.pneumocephalus 3.fractures of the floor of both orbits.4.fractures of the medial walls of the maxiallry sinuses bilaterally.

text: moderate mucosal thickening is seen within the left maxillary sinus; the thickening is diffuse and extends into the left ostiomeatal complex and the infundibulum, obstructing these regions.there is also milder mucosal thickening within the ethmoid air cells and the inferior right frontal sinus.minimal inferior right maxillary sinus mucosal thickening is present; the ostium is patent on this side.there is a small left nasal septal spur.the sphenoid sinus is normal in appearance.there is atherosclerotic calcification of the cavernous carotid arteries.the lamina paprycea are intact.the cribiform plates are parallel and there is no pneumatization of the anterior clinoid processes.
summary: sinus mucosal thickening, predominantly within the left maxillary and ethmoid sinuses.given the clinical history, the findings likely represent sinusitis.

text: the linear fracture of the occipital bone on the right is again identified.there are small amounts of fluid density material within the right mastoid air cells, but there is no fracture plane identified extending through the sphenoid sinus or petrous bones.the ossicles appear to be intact.there is a small amount of soft tissue thickening in the left maxillary sinus.
summary: non-depressed linear occipital fracture without other obvious fracture, though a small amount of fluid attenuation is present within the right mastoid air cells as well as the sphenoid sinus.

text: again is seen the subcutaneous hematoma over the right malar eminence and zygomatic arch.there is no definite evidence of fracture.the right maxillary sinus is properly aerated.a nasogastric tube is in place.there is some increased soft tissue density in the ethmoid and sphenoid sinuses possibly related to the tube.there is no evidence of orbital fracture.
summary: no evidence of fracture.it is noted on the head ct the right- sided subcutaneous hematoma appears to be slightly larger than the previous cts given differences in technique and position.

text: the frontal, ethmoid, sphenoid, and maxillary sinuses are normally aerated.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.the cribriform plates are ymmetric.the sphenoid sinus septum inserts anterior to the right carotid groove.the infundibula of the osteomeatal complexes are patent.
summary: no evidence of acute or chronic sinusitis.

text: there is a fracture of the left mandibular condyle with medial and inferior displacement of the majority of the condyle.a linear lucency traverses the lateral margin of the temporal glenoid labrum, possibly representing a suture or fracture of the glenoid rim.a linear lucency is also seen traversing the mid portion of the styloid process, consistent with a probable nondisplaced fracture at this locale.no other fractures are identified.the visualized portions of the cervical spine demonstrate normal alignment.the mastoid air cells are well aerated.mucosal thickening and/or fluid is present within the ethmoid and sphenoid sinuses bilaterally.there is a large left nasal septal spur.
summary: there is a displaced fracture of the left mandibular condyle and probable fractures of the styloid process and the glenoid labrum.

text: there is a small amount of fluid present within the sphenoid sinus.there is also trace fluid within the right maxillary sinus.the remainder of the paranasal sinuses are clear.the patient is intubated.
summary: small amount of fluid within the sphenoid and right maxillary sinus.

text: reference is made to the brain mri from ___.there is mucosal thickening in the left frontal sinus.the right frontal sinus is not pneumatized.there is extensive mucosal thickening/opacification in the ethmoid air cells.there is mucosal thickening in both maxillary sinuses, with a possible air fluid level on the left.there is near complete opacification of the sphenoid sinuses, along with mucosal thickening.the nasal septum deviates to the right, with a rightward spur.very limited evaluation of intracranial structures is unremarkable.
summary: extensive sinus disease as described above.the patient is intubated, and the abnormalities may be due simply to intubation, or to bacterial or fungal sinusitis.

text: there are three probable mucus retention cysts in the right maxillary sinus.the left maxillary sinus, sphenoid sinuses, ethmoid air cells, and frontal sinuses are clear.the nasal septum bows slightly to the right, and has a spur which impinges on the inferior turbinate.the sphenoid septum inserts on the right carotid sulcus.the cribriform plates are level.the lamina papyracea is intact bilaterally.there is no aeration of the anterior clinoid processes or the right optic struct.there is partial pneumatization of the left optic strut.a right sided ng tube is present.
summary: three probable mucus retention cysts in the right maxillary sinus.no evidence of acute sinusitis.

text: there is opacification of the sphenoid sinus with a rounded area of higher attenuation with dense peripheral areas of calcification.the remaining paranasal sinuses are clear.there are osseous abnormalities.there is calcification of the cavernous carotid arteries.there is brain atrophy.the remaining bones are unremarkable.
summary: opacification of sphenoid sinus with a rounded, calcified lesion.this is of uncertain etiology, but may represent chronic fungal infection.a neoplasm is not excluded and imaging with sedation using mri pre and post- gadollinium with fat saturation (similar to a pituitary protocol) should be considered for improved characterization.

text: there are numerous fractures seen.there is a comminuted fracture of the nasal septum.there are comminuted fractures of the nasal bones bilaterally.there are comminuted fractures of the anterior and medial walls of the maxillary sinuses bilaterally.in addition, the roof of the maxillary sinuses bilaterally has been compromised with fractures, as well.the lateral wall of the right maxillary sinus is fractured, as well, as is the lateral wall of the left maxillary sinus.there is fluid, air, and hemorrhage in the maxillary sinuses bilaterally.there is fluid in the sphenoid sinuses bilaterally, given the setting of trauma, raises a suspicion of basal skull fractures.there is a suggestion of fracture involving the floor of the right orbit.possible fractures involving the roofs of both orbits.there is no entrapment of the extraocular muscles per se, and no retroorbital fluid collections are identified.direct coronal ct images recommended when the patient is stable.there is soft-tissue swelling, and air in the soft tissues overlying the maxillary sinuses, as well as overlying the right orbit.
summary: preseptal air in the soft tissues of the right eye.numerous facial fractures, as described above.

text: the patient remains intubated, and there is trace amount of fluid layering within the right maxillary sinus.there is mucosal thickening within the sphenoid, ethmoid, frontal and left maxillary sinuses as well.there is a small amount of fluid layering within both middle ear cavities bilaterally, and there is is fluid within the mastoid air cells bilaterally as well.
summary: mild to moderate mucosal thickening within the paranasal sinuses.trace fluid in the right maxillary sinus.fluid within the middle ear cavities and mastoid air cells bilaterally.

text: the nasopharyngeal and upper oropharyngeal soft tissues are swollen, and this is evident both on the ct images and scout radiograph of this study.numerous small lymph nodes are identified in the portions of the neck examined.there is almost complete opacification of the maxillary sinuses, with fluid levels evident.there is complete opacification of the sphenoid air cells.there is a sphenoid septum which inserts on the right carotid groove.there is fluid and soft tissue thickening in many of the ethmoid air cells.mucosal thickening and fluid is also present in the frontal sinus, greater on the left than the right.there is complete opacification of the mastoid air cells and middle ___ cavities.there is also opacification of pneumatized petrous apical air cells.the orbits appear grossly normal.
summary: paranasal sinus and mastoid fluid and opacification, which is consistent with sinusitis, but may also occur with prolonged intubation.additionally, there is prominence of the pharyngeal soft tissues, consistent with inflammatory or infectious process.

text: this study is being redictated on ___ due to rtas malfunction.there are fractures of the right lateral orbital wall, orbital floor, and inferior orbital rim.there is a fracture through the inferior aspect of the lamina papyracea, as well as through the nasolacrimal duct on the right.the orbital roof is intact.there are fractures of the nasal bones.there is a horizontal fracture through the right aspect of the maxilla extending into the nasal cavity.there is a fracture of the right anterior maxillary sinus wall, and comminuted fractures of the posterior lateral maxillary sinus wall, with osseous fragments within the sinus.there is a fracture of the right zygomatic arch as well.there are fluid levels within the sphenoid sinuses, right maxillary sinus, ethmoid air cells, and mucosal thickening within the frontal sinuses and the left maxillary sinus.the mandible appears intact.visualized mastoid air cells are clear.there is no herniation of the orbital fat.
summary: multiple fractures as described above.

text: the paranasal sinuses are normally aerated with no mucosal thickening or air-fluid levels identified.the nasal septum is slightly deviated to the left.sphenoid sinus septum is midline with insertion at the midline.
summary: the sinuses are clear.there is no evidence of acute sinusitis.

text: extensive fractures are noted through the facial bones with the appearance of a mixed type ii/iii le fort fracture.specifically, the fracture network on the left extends to the inner and outer tables of the frontal sinuses where there is comminution.the fracture plane extends inferiorly to involve the roof of the orbit, the floor of the orbit, and the laminae papyraceae.the fracture plane extends posteriorly through the ethmoid air cells and across the sphenoid sinus and the body of the sphenoid bone and exits along the anterior sella turcica and right inferolateral sella turcica.the fracture continues across the midline, extending posteriorly through the right aspect of the clivus and exits at the foramen magnum.note that the fracture plane appears to traverse the medial-most aspect of the right carotid canal before exiting the foramen magnum.note that the fractures on the left also pass through the left maxillary sinus.on the right, the fracture plane extends through the maxillary sinus but does not appear to involve the right orbit.the fracture plane as it extends posteriorly passes through the right pterygoid plate and across the right sphenoid sinus where the fracture appears to join with the fracture network involving the left facial bones.there is bilateral proptosis slightly greater on the left without frank hemorrhage into the orbits.there is extensive opacification of the paranasal sinuses with air-fluid consistent with associated hemorrhages.there is no evidence of pneumocephalus, though air is seen tracking in the soft tissues over the left forehead.
summary: mixed le fort type fracture which extends through the orbit on the left (type iii) and through the maxillary sinuses on the right (type ii).of note, the fracture plane appear to traverse the medial-most right carotid canal.also of note, the fracture plane extends through both tables of the calvarium at the left frontal sinus, allowing communication between the cranial vault and the frontal sinus.also of note, the fracture plane extends to involve the sella turcica, crosses the sphenoid bone, and exits at the foramen magnum.please see report of the head ct and cervical spine performed on the same day for other findings.

text: intracranial pathology is seen and is described under clip ___.this exam was performed several minutes before the current study.there is fracture of the medial and inferior wall of the right orbit.the medial rectus muscle herniates through the defect in the lamina papyracea.there is herniation of extraconal fat through the inferior orbital fracture but the inferior rectus muscle remains within the orbit.no hematoma is seen within the orbit but there is mild proptosis of the left globe.there is fracture of the medial wall of the right maxillary sinus and the maxillary sinus is opacified with high density blood products.high density fluid is seen within the left sphenoid sinus.there may be a small fracture along the posterolateral portion of the sinus, abutting the carotid groove.there is a transverse fracture of the petrous portion of the left temporal bone and fluid is seen within the left external auditory canal and middle ear.there are comminuted fractures of both nasal bones and hemorrhage is seen within both ethmoid air cells.there is no fracture of the pterygoid plates.the patient has an ng tube and an endotracheal tube.there is a fracture of the mandible.the tmj's are intact.
summary: multiple right sided facial fractures including fractures of the right lamina papyracea and orbital floor.the right medial rectus muscle herniates outside of the orbit.fluid within the left sphenoid air cell.there is possibly a fracture along the posterolateral aspect of the sinus, along the carotid groove.multiple nasal bone fractures.no mandibular fracture.nondisplaced transverse fracture of the left temporal bone.

text: there are no visible fractures of the mandible.there is a foreign body, most consistent with a gauze extending from outside the patient along the right side of the tongue.at the level of the angle of the right mandible, there are multiple vascular coils.there is also an adjacent hyperdense collection, which could represent blood, extending along the inferior aspect of the right mandible and medial to the right medial pteryoid muscle, within the masticator space.the paranasal sinuses contain multiple air fluid levels, presumably secretions and/or hemorrhage.
summary: no acute fracture.there is a surgical sponge or gauze and a hyperdense collection seen along the right side of the mandible.probable hematoma, involving the right sided portion of the submanidular, sublingual and masticator spaces.

text: there is no evidence of fluid within the sinuses to suggest sinusitis.there is a small polyp versus mucous retention cyst within the anterior aspect of the right maxillary sinus as well as within the posterior aspect of the left sphenoid sinus.the osteal meatal units are patent bilaterally.the left cribiform plate is perhaps 1 mm higher than that on the right.the lamina paprycea are intact.the sphenoid sinus septum inserts adjacent to both carotid grooves.the soft tissues are grossly unremarkable.
summary: no evidence of sinusitis.

text: there is a right nasoenteric tube.dependent fluid is seen within the right maxillary sinus antrum.lobulated low-density material is also seen within the dependent portions of the sphenoid sinus, consistent with fluid and minimal mucosal thickening.the contents of the orbits are normal in appearance.no osseous erosions are identified.
summary: fluid seen within the dependent portions of the right maxillary sinus and sphenoid sinus.given recent intubation, it is difficult to determine whether this is related to inflammation or infection.

text: there are three tiny rounded mucosal densities in the maxillary sinuses which probably represent mucous retention cysts or polyps.there is no evidence of sinus fluid.the ostiomeatal complexes are clear.there is minimal mucosal thickening in the ethmoid air cells.there is a small amount of secretion in the sphenoid sinus.the frontal sinuses are clear.visualized portions of the mastoid air cells and middle ear cavities are clear.
summary: no definite evidence of acute sinusitis, though there is a small amount of secretion in the sphenoid sinus.dr.___ was phoned with the findings of this study at 2:25 pm on ___.

text: there are bilateral fractures of the anterior maxilla above the aveolar ridge, tracking to the anterior wall of the maxillary sinus.there is widening of the right zygomatic/maxillary suture.fracture lines extend posteriorly and there are comminuted fractures of both pterygoid plates.high density hemorrhage products are seen within the nasal cavity, sphenoid sinuses, maxillary sinuses, ethmoid air cells, and frontal sinuses.there is stippled air within the subcutaneous tissues of the face.there is no evidence of mandibular fracture though the left tmj has been excluded from the exam.no orbital fractures are seen.however, there are tiny air droplets in the inferior orbits bilaterally, raising the possibility of small orbital floor fractures which are not identified on this study.no fracture lines are seen within the skull base.review of the bone window images from the head ct (clip ___) shows no fluid within the inner ears or mastoid air cells, suggesting no temporal bone fracture.note is made of an endotracheal tube.
summary: fractures of the maxilla, walls of the maxillary sinus, and pterygoid plates as described above.fluid in the sphenoid sinuses is explained by the maxillary fractures and no fractures are seen within the skull base.

text: there is a comminuted fracture of the left orbital floor involving the path of the infraorbital nerve.the fracture extends back to the pterygopalatine fossa.there is a large fragment depressed into the left maxillary sinus, which is nearly entirely opacified with blood.the orbital rim appears intact.there is a small amount of hematoma in the orbit along the lamina papyracea and along the lateral orbital wall.the hematoma does not extend back to the orbital apex at this time.there is proptosis of the left globe, a large periorbital hematoma, and a small amount of intraorbital gas.there is a nondisplaced fracture of the posterolateral wall of the left maxillary sinus.the medial wall may be fractured posteriorly near the middle meatus.there is blood within the nasal cavity and left ethmoid air cells.no definite fracture of the lamina papyracea is seen.the nasal septum is deviated to the right, which is likely chronic.there is minimal mucosal thickening in the frontal and right maxillary sinuses.a small amount of fluid is seen in the left side of the sphenoid sinus.
summary: comminuted fracture of the left orbital floor, with depressed fragment and small amount of intraorbital hematoma.there is no direct compression of the orbital nerve, but the globe is proptotic.fracture of the posterolateral wall of the left maxillary sinus extending back to the pterygopalatine fossa.fracture of the medial wall of the left maxillary sinus in the region of the middle meatus and ostiomeatal complex.

text: surgical screws and plates are again noted within the mandible, right maxilla, and nose.these fracture fragments again remain in near anatomic alignment.again seen are extensive fractures involving primarily the right facial bones.comminuted fractures involving the superior, inferior, medial, and lateral walls of the right orbit are present.there is continued lateral displacement of the right globe which is intact.comminuted inferior rim fracture of the left orbit is also present.again identified are fractures through both pterygoid plates with extension of the fracture line on the right side through the right mastoid process with opacification of the right mastoid air cells.the anterior and lateral walls of the right maxillary sinus are completely destroyed and only a few remnant fragments are seen.fractures are also identified through the anterior, lateral, and medial walls of the left maxillary sinus.fractures are also present through the mandible symphysis, right zygomatic arch, nasal septum, and both ethmoid sinuses.a fracture is seen through the right temporomandibular joint with lateral dislocation of the right mandibular condyle.there continues to be extensive soft tissue swelling and hematoma within the right side of the face.there is extensive opacification involving all of the paranasal sinuses.the floor of the anterior fossa is intact.
summary: extensive fractures involving primarily the right-sided facial bones as described above.

text: no fractures are identified.there is mild to moderate mucosal thickening of the right maxillary sinuse as demonstrated on the sinus ct.the upper cervical spine (through c5) are unremarkable.no soft tissue abnormalities are seen.a portion of the nasogastric and oral tracheal tubes are visualized.
summary: no evidence for fracture.mild to moderate mucosal thickening of the right maxillary sinus.sinusitis cannot be excluded.no findings to suggest an abscess.if there is strong clinical concern for an abscess, repeat imaging with intravenous contrast could be considered.

text: there is a slightly distracted fracture through the right aspect of the c2 vertebral body extending into the right foramen transversarium with slight posterior displacement as well as a fracture through the lamina of c2 on the left.a linear nondisplaced fracture extends through the inferior orbital rim on the right traversing the inferior wall of the right maxillary sinus as well.there is no evidence of orbital entrapment.there is a comminuted fracture of the squamous portion of the right temporal bone with several depressed fragments extending approximately 5 mm intracranially.a linear nondisplaced fracture of the right frontal bone extends into the superior margin of the right orbit.there is a massive soft tissue defect within the high right frontal region with evidence of radiopaque foreign bodies scattered throughout the soft tissues of the right frontal and temporal regions.there is mucosal thickening within the left maxillary sinus as well as an air fluid level within the right maxillary sinuses.the ethmoid air cells are partially opacified and there is evidence of mucosal thickening within both sphenoid sinuses.both zygomatic arches are intact.no evidence of mandibular fracture.the lamina papyrcea are intact.
summary: linear fracture of the right frontal bone extending into the superior orbital rim, linear fracture of the right inferior orbital rim with no evidence of entrapment, comminuted fracture of the squamous portion of the right temporal bone with slight depression of comminuted bone fragments, and multiple cervical spine fractures as described on a ct report of the cervical spine from the same day.massive soft tissue injury involving the right frontal and temporal soft tissues with radiopaque foreign bodies scattered throughout.

text: there is a mild degree of mucosal thickening in the inferior right maxillary sinus and in the sphenoid sinus.no fluid levels are identified.the ethmoid and frontal sinuses are clear.the nasal cavity is clear.the nasal septum is roughly midline.there is a ngt which extends through the left nasal cavity.no lytic or destructive changes of the bones are identified.the orbits are grossly normal.
summary: mild sinus mucosal thickening without evidence of acute sinusitis.

text: there is a small mucus retention cyst in the right maxillary floor.the left maxillary sinus, sphenoid sinuses, frontal sinuses, and ethmoid air cells are clear.the coronal views are extremely limited.there is no aeration of the anterior clinoid processes, or the optic struts.lamina papyracea appears intact, but evaluation is severely limited.the septum deviates slightly to the right anteriorly.the sphenoid septum inserts on the right carotid sulcus.the cribriform plates were not definitely visualized, but are likely level.the infundibula and ostea of the ostiomeatal complexes could not be properly evaluated.
summary: no evidence of acute sinusitis.

text: there are fractures involving the medial and inferior right orbital walls.the medial wall fracture is depressed and the medial rectus muscle herniates into the ethmoid sinus along with the laminae papyraceae.there is also an inferiorly displaced orbital floor fracture without evidence of muscle entrapment.there is associated blood within the right maxillary sinus.there also appears to be a small amount of hemorrhage immediately posterior to the right globe.there is proptosis of the right globe.there are air and high-attenuation foreign bodies in the soft tissues overlying the right maxilla and right forehead.over the right forehead, the skin and soft tissues are displaced away from the cranium consistent with a degloving injury.the left maxillary sinus is clear.there are air-fluid levels in the ethmoid air cells.there is a small amount of thickening in the sphenoid sinus and a suggestion of an air-fluid level in the sphenoid sinus.there is no evidence of skull base fractures.
summary: comminuted fractures involving the inferior and medial right orbital floor.the medial rectus muscle appears herniated into the ethmoid sinus.please see above for further description.

text: 3d reformatted images were not available at the time of dictation.interval surgical reconstruction of the nose, mandible, and right maxilla with screws and plates visualized stabilizing these bones.there is near anatomic alignment of the fracture fragments.the right temporal mandibular joint, however, is still dislocated with the mandibular condyle laterally displaced from the condylar fossa.there has also been interval repair of a right scalp laceration with a drainage catheter now present in the subcutaneous tissues of the scalp lateral to the frontal and parietal bones.a thin subcentimeter linear metallic density object is seen in the region of the right pytergoid plate.this may be related to a surgical suture.surgical material is also seen posterior to the right mandible within the soft tissues best appreciated on sagittal reconstructions.the remainder of the extensive fractures as detailed on the prior study of ___ are largely unchanged in appearance.a fracture fragment remains within the right orbit.the right globe continues to be laterally displaced from the orbit.
summary: interval surgical reconstruction of the nose, mandible, and maxilla with near anatomic alignment of the fracture fragments.unchanged appearance to the remainder of the fractures as described on previous study ___.

text: there is moderate mucosal thickening of the right maxillary sinus.the remainder of the paranasal sinuses are clear.an ng tube is in place.the anterior coronoid processes are not pneumatized.the cribriform plates are symmetric.
summary: mild-moderate mucosal thickening of the right maxillary sinus.sinusitis cannot be excluded in the appropriate clinical context.

text: there is an extensive crush injury with resultant comminuted fractures of predominantly the right-sided facial bones.specifically, there are comminuted fractures of the superior, lateral, medial, and inferior orbit.the nasal bones are fractuted and the nose is deformed.there are fractures of both pterygoid plates, both maxillary sinuses, ethmoid bones, and the right zygomatic arch.the right temporomandibular joint is dislocated and laterally displaced.the right globe is extruded and laterally displaced from the right orbit.within the orbit there is a large fracture fragment that is adjacent to the optic nerve and medial rectus muscle which laterally displaces both the nerve and muscle.the right optic nerve appears stretched when compared with the left optic nerve.the nerve and muscles, however, appear to be intact.there is a diastatic and displaced fracture of the mandible extending from the right condyle across the midline into the inferior left mandible.there is blood within both maxillary and ethmoid sinuses, and right mastoid air cells.the left orbit, temporomandibular joint, and zygomatic arch appear preserved without evidence of fracture.there is marked right-sided soft tissue deformity and hematoma.there is subcutaneous air throughout the soft tissues of the right face as well as in the soft tissues of the posterior oropharynx and retropharyngeal space.the patient is intubated and an ngt is also in place.
summary: multiple comminuted fractures of the right sided facial bones and orbit as described above.extrusion and lateral displacement of the right globe with a fracture fragment noted in the right orbit.this lies adjacent to the optic nerve and medial rectus muscle.the nerve and muscles appear intact.displaced mandibular fracture preservation of the left orbit and left zygoma.these findings were discussed with dr.___ on ___ at 1:30 p.m.

text: there is fracture of the floor of the right orbit with herniation of orbital fat into the right maxillary sinus.the right inferior rectus muscle also herniates into the sinus.additionally, there is fracture of the medial wall of the right maxillary sinus and high density blood products seen layering within.there is proptosis of the right globe, which is displaced anteriorly and laterally.extraconal, high density hemorrhage is seen superior and medial to the right globe.there is no stranding of the fat within the intraconal regions or around the optic nerve.the pterygoid plates are intact.the tmj's are nondislocated.the lamina papyracea are intact.the imaged portions of the mandible are not fractured.no fluid is seen within the mastoid air cells or middle ear canal.there is some circumferential thickening within the right sphenoid sinus, suggestive of chronic sinusitis.
summary: fractures of the right orbital floor and medial wall of the right maxillary sinus with herniations of the orbital fat and inferior rectus muscle into the maxillary sinus.extraconal hematoma superior and medial to the right globe resulting in anteriolateral proptosis.preseptal soft tissue edema does not extend into the orbit.

text: there is fluid within the right maxillary sinus.there is a small amount of fluid within the right osteomeatal complex, although it appears patent.the osteomeatal complex is patent on the left.the middle turbinates are pneumatized bilaterally.there is fluid within the right pneumatized middle turbinate.there is partial ethmoid opacification bilaterally.there are fluid or retention cysts within the sphenoid and frontal sinuses also, right sided greater than left.there is mucosal thickening of the right sided middle and inferior turbinate.compared to the previous study, these air fluid levels within the right maxillary sinus, right sphenoid and right ethmoid air cells are new.
summary: interval development of fluid levels within the maxillary, ethmoid, sphenoid and frontal air cells.these findings are consistent with sinus inflammatory disease.

text: the overall appearance of the sinuses is unchanged from the previous study 8 days earlier.there is again fluid within the right maxillary sinus, right, pneumatized middle turbinate, bilateral ethmoid and frontal sinuses.the severity of these findings is not changed since the previous study.again there is no evidence of bony destruction.
summary: unchanged appearance of fluid levels within the maxillary, ethmoid, sphenoid and frontal air cells.persistent sinus inflammatory disease.

text: there has been interval placement of a metallic plate over the left-sided mandibular fracture with multiple screws.a small amount of adjacent air and soft tissue swelling most likely represents postoperative changes.there also appears to be two screws that have been placed within the maxilla.the mandibular plate appears to be joining the mandibular fracture fragments.the bilateral condylar fractures and dislocation of the condyles from the temporomandibular joint spaces are unchanged.there is opacification and air- fluid levels seen within the frontal, sphenoid, ethmoid, and maxillary air cells.the frontal, ethmoid and maxillary opacification is new since the previous study.there is also fluid seen within the middle ear cavities bilaterally.
summary: interval plating of left mandibular fracture, as well as screw placement into the maxilla.persistent fractures of both mandibular condyles, which are displaced out of the temporomandibular joint cavities.interval opacification with air-fluid levels within all paranasal sinuses and middle ears bilaterally.

text: there is a depressed fracture of the left orbital floor with an associated downward excursion of the left inferior rectus muscle, but no displacement into the maxillary sinus.air is present in the extraconal orbital fat.there is no frank evidence of orbital fat herniation into the left maxillary sinus, which contains fluid and blood, but clinical correlation is necessary to exclude the possibility of ocular muscular entrapment.there is fluid in multiple left- sided ethmoid air cells, though a a fracture of the lamina papyracea is not identified.there is a fracture of the posterior left maxillary sinus wall.there is fluid in the sphenoid sinuses.the mandible appears intact, but there is anterior subluxation of the right mandibular condyle, seen best on the sagittal images.note is made that the patient's mouth is not open during scanning.there is a fracture of the left nasal bone.no skull base or sphenoid fractures are seen.there is soft tissue swelling in the left frontal region.note is also made that the right styloid process appears slightly longer than the left.an additional osseous fragment is seen more inferiorly off the tip of the styloid process.this could represent a fracture of the left styloid process.
summary: orbital floor fracture with depressed fragment in the left maxillary sinus.correlate clinically for evidence of muscle entrapment.fracture of the posterior maxillary sinus wall.left nasal bone fracture.results were discussed with dr.___ ___, at 1:45 am on ___.

text: as identified on the ct scan of the brain, there is a fracture through the occipital bone extending anterior-posterior, just left of midline.again identified is a fracture through the sphenoid (near midline) and dorsum sella (which is just to the right of midline).temporal bones are intact.the frontal sinuses are intact, though they are opacified.the lamina papyracea and orbital bony structures are intact.orbital contents appear normal.the anterior clinoids are intact.there are nasal bone fractures, age indeterminate.the maxillary sinuses and maxilla appear to be intact.the zygomatic arches are not fractured.
summary: occipital and sphenoid fractures as described on the ct scan of the brain.nasal bone fracture of indeterminate age.no fractures through the paranasal sinuses, temporal bones or mastoids are identified.

text: there is motion on the axial images and the coronal reconstructions are not of good quality.the frontal, ethmoid and maxillary sinuses are clear.there is minimal membrane thickening or a small air fluid level in the left lateral aspect of the sphenoid sinuses.the patient does have an orogastric or tracheal tube in place, so that the significance of this finding is not clear.
summary: minimal thickening or fluid level in the lateral aspect of the sphenoid sinus.the significance is indeterminate.see above discussion.

text: there is no evidence of facial bone fracture.there are no air fluid levels within the sinuses to suggest an occult fracture.mild hematoma is again noted anterior to the right frontal bone.limited imaging of the brain redemonstrates prior right frontal infarction with extension of the right lateral ventricle.blood is noted coursing along the left falx.
summary: no evidence of fracture.

text: there is worsening opacification of the right maxillary, both ethmoid, sphenoid and right frontal sinuses by mucosal thickening.there is obstruction to the right osteometal unit.infection is a consideration.there is soft tissue prominence in the region of the nasopharynx which could be due to mucosal thickening or adenoidal hypertrophy.bone remodeling is seen with slight expansion of the lateral right maxillary wall indicating chronicity of the sinus infection.correlation with ent exam would be helpful.there is minor nasal septal deviation unchanged.
summary: significant pan sinus disease, especially involving the sphenoid and right frontal sinuses which were partially clear on the previous exam of ___.there is total opacification of the right maxillary sinus indicative of obstruction to the right osteomeatal unit.correlation with ent exam would be recommended.followup is suggested.

text: there is fluid and thickening in the maxillary sinuses bilaterally.there is thickening of the ethmoid, frontal, and sphenoid sinuses as well.there is fluid in the mastoid air cells bilaterally.the partially visualized brain parenchyma is unremarkable.
summary: paranasal and mastoid sinusitis.

text: the maxillary, frontal, sphenoid, and ethmoid sinuses are clear with no air fluid levels or mucosal thickening to suggest acute sinusitis.both ostiomeatal units are patent.right anterior clinoid process is pneumatized.cribriform plates are symmetric in height.there are multiple septae within the sphenoid sinuses.the visualized portions of the mastoid air cells are clear.the lamina papyracea is intact.the nasal septum is midline.
summary: no evidence of acute sinusitis.

text: again noted are the multiple facial fractures as described on the prior report of the ct of the facial bones done ___.micro-plates and screws are noted to affix the parasymphyseal mandibular fracture, hard palate, nasal apeture, and maxillary sinuses.the parasymphyseal fracture, at the posterior cortex of the mandible, show a few mm of offset.the paranasal sinuses are opacified and there is diffuse soft tissue swelling.
summary: status post open reduction/internal fixation of multiple facial fractures.

text: there is marked opacification within the left maxillary and right sphenoid sinuses as well as a lesser degree of opacification within the left sphenoid sinus, the ethmoid air cells bilaterally.the mastoid air cells, frontal sinuses, and right maxillary sinus are clear.the lamina papyracea and orbital floors are intact.the nasal septum is midline with no spurs.the ostiomeatal units are patent bilaterally.the cribriform plates are symmetric in height.the patient is intubated.there is no evidence of bone destruction.
summary: opacification within the paranasal sinuses which is most prominent within the left maxillary and right sphenoid sinus.this finding may be explained by the patient's intubated status.

text: there is complete opacification of the right maxillary sinus which is filled with blood.there is a fluid level within the left maxillary sinus as well as the left sphenoid sinus.the nasal cavity is opacified.there is fluid within the left mastoid air cells.there is a segmental depressed fracture of the right zygomatic arch.there is a comminuted fracture of the lateral margin of the right orbit.these comminuted bone fragments passed immediately adjacent to the lateral rectus muscle on the right.there is a comminuted fracture of the right orbital floor.the inferior rectus muscle and the inferior oblique muscle pass immediately above this comminuted fracture of the right orbital floor.there is no definite evidence of entrapment of the extraoccular muscles; however, entrapment cannot be excluded.there is a depressed comminuted fracture of the lateral margin of the right maxillary sinus with bone fragments which are buckled medially.there is a fracture of the anterior maxillary wall and the malar eminence is depressed.there is a comminuted fracture of the ascending ramus of the left mandible with complete disruption of the articular surface of the mandible within the temporomandibular joint on the left.there is gas in the right cavernous sinus.there is fluid level within the left sphenoid sinus as well as opacification within the left mastoid air cells.an occult basilar skull fracture on the left cannot be excluded.there is a massive amount of soft tissue swelling over the right face with a large amount of subcutaneous gas.there is evidence of bullous change within the visualized portions of the lung apices.there is extensive motion artifact within the visualized portion of the upper cervical spine.
summary: severely comminuted fractures involving the lateral margin of the right orbit as well as the right orbital floor.clinical correlation is recommended to exclude entrapment of the lateral and inferior extraoccular muscles to exclude entrapment.depressed comminuted fracture of the lateral wall of the right maxillary sinus with extensive opacification of the right maxillary sinus by hemorrhage.fluid levels within the left sphenoid sinus and left maxillary sinus.an occult basilar skull fracture in these regions cannot be excluded.comminuted fracture of the ascending ramus of the mandible on the left.the most severely comminuted portion of this fracture involves the articular surface of the mandible in the temporomandibular joint on the left.extensive soft tissue swelling with subcutaneous gas over the right facial region.

text: this study is limited secondary to motion artifact and image processing.the opacification of the left mastoid air cells and left middle ear cavity has lessened.there is a rounded opacification present in the left sphenoid sinus consistent with either polyp or retention cyst.the maxillary sinuses, ethmoid sinuses, and frontal sinuses are well aerated.limited images of the brain show no hydrocephalus, or shift of normally midline structures.
summary: limited study secondary to motion artifact in image processing.interval decrease in opacification of the left mastoid air cells and left middle ear cavity.

text: anterior nasal packs are in place.there are air-fluid levels in the maxillary sinuses and there is considerable abnormal soft tissue density in virtually all the paranasal sinuses except the frontal sinuses.there are air- fluid levels also in the sphenoid sinus.there is high density in the maxillary sinuses attributable to blood product.there is increased soft tissue density in the posterior nasopharynx as identified on the head ct scout film.some of this appears to be accumulated secretions but some of it may represent blood products since it is slightly high in density.there is no evidence of bone erosion.the pterygo-palatine fossae are not expanded.
summary: abnormalities within the sinuses and nasopharynx as described most likely related to the presence of anterior nasal packs.a nasopharyngeal mass is not entirely excluded.

text: the mastoid, ethmoid, sphenoid, and frontal sinuses are well aerated without evidence of mucosal thickening or air-fluid levels.the ostiomeatal units are patent bilaterally.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.the cribriform plates are slightly uneven in height, with the left being lower than the right.
summary: well aerated paranasal sinuses without evidence of mucosal thickening or air-fluid level.

text: please note that the patient is intubated.air fluid levels and mucosal thickening is present within the sphenoid sinuses.slight mucosal thickening is present within the left maxillary sinus as well as within the ethmoid air cells.the osteal meatal units are patent.the nasal septum is slightly deviated to the left with a spur.the lamina paprycea are intact.the orbital floors are also within normal limits.there is no evidence of bone destruction or bone erosion.
summary: mucosal thickening within the left maxillary sinus.air fluid levels and mucosal thickening within the sphenoid sinuses.please note that the findings occur in the presence of patient intubation.

text: please note that on the current examination, the initial axial acquisition was performed with corrected adaptation.thus, the patient's right side is displayed as if it is the left side.correlation with previous studies demonstrate that there were orbital and maxillary sinus fractures on the right, seen on multiple prior studies.thus, for thet purpose of this report, i interpret the prior studies to have been labeled correctly.there has been repair of an orbital floor and inferior orbital rim fracture on the right.there is continued complete opacification of the right maxillary sinus.there are sharp fracture lines noted involving the wall of the maxillary sinus, unusual for fractures that are six months old.there is also a sharply marginated fracture of the right zygomatic arch, again unusual for a six month old fracture.there is a small fracture through the squamous portions of the right temporal bone.this appears unchanged since the prior examination.however, the zygomatic arch fracture on the right appears new.the study was tailored for examination of the facial bones, not the temporal bone.however, the left temporal bone fracture is no longer visualized.coronal reformatted images demonstrate reconstruction of the right orbital floor with the inferior rectus muscle appearing slightly enlarged, but not entrapped.no orbital contents are seen herniated into the defect in the orbital floor created by the fracture.there is extensive soft tissue swelling overlying the right malar eminence.
summary: status-post repair of right orbital floor fracture.apparently new fractures of the right maxillary sinus.apparently new right zygomatic arch fracture.please note that several of the image sets are mislabeled with the right side incorrectly identified as the left.

text: there is a fracture of the posterolateral maxillary wall on the left side with an air-fluid level in the maxillary sinus.there is no evidence of orbital fracture.the zygomatic arch is intact.the lamina papyracea are intact.the nasal bones are slightly deformed but there is no definite evidence of acute fracture.
