text: fluid levels are present in the maxillary sinuses, and in the left sphenoid sinus, with layering hemorrhagic products.the mastoid air cells are clear.there is posterior buckling of the anterior wall of the right maxillary sinus.there is also a a non-displaced fracture of the right inferior orbital wall, without herniation of fat or muscle.the medial orbital wall shows multiple small irregularities in the bony contour, suspicious for subtle fractures, also implied by the presence of a small focus of medial post-septal air in the orbit.multiple minimally or non-displaced lucencies through the body of the sphenoid bone, along the sphenoid sinus roof, are noted in the midline.in the nearby optic canal, there is a tiny bubble of air.on the opposite side of the canal adjacent to the left anterior clinoid process, there is also a tiny osseous fragment which is probably also related to the sphenoid fractures.the left optic nerve is not imaged on this study, but the intraorbital contents are otherwise unremarkable.there is a coronal fracture extending from the greater ___ of the sphenoid, at the site of a 1 cm thick epidural hematoma in the right middle cranial fossa superiorly, and perhaps involving the right parietal bone as well.there is also a nondisplaced fracture in the left greater sphenoid ___.an oblique fracture within the greater ___ of the right sphenoid is also present.there is also a fracture line through the frontal process of the right zygoma.
summary: fractures of the greater sphenoid wings and the anterior body overlying the sphenoid bone.the appearance includes a tiny osseous fragment and bubble of air in the left optic canal.correlation with clinical factors concerning any potential for optic nerve injury is recommended, and consideration of mr if further imaging of the soft tissue structures is needed.epidural hematoma associated with fracture in the right greater sphenoid ___.nondisplaced fracture of the anterior process of the right zygoma.nondisplaced inferior and medial fractures of the right orbit.fluid levels in the maxillary sinuses and in the sphenoid sinus consistent with hemorrhage.

text: prior right-sided craniotomy.there is a left frontal scalp contusion and left preseptal periorbital soft tissue swelling.the globe is intact.no retrobulbar hematoma.the paranasal sinuses are clear.no acute facial fractures are appreciated.chronic intraparenchymal contusions (see head ct report).coronal images confirm that the orbital floor is intact.

text: there is diffuse opacification of the ethmoid air cells, and fluid- fluid levels in the maxillary sinuses consistent with hemorrhage.the presence of fluid-fluid levels could raise the question of whether coagulopathy is present.there also is hemorrhage in the nasopharynx.there are comminuted fractures of the medial walls of the maxillary sinuses with impaction and the vomer and nasal bones.there is air in the inferior orbits on the right which is extraconal and although not well visualized, non- displaced right inferior orbital wall fracture is suspected, although herniation of the inferior rectus muscle and orbital fat are not demonstrated.the mastoid air cells are clear.minimally displaced fracture of the right anterior maxilla is also observed.
summary: non-displaced right inferior orbital wall fracture, with extraconal air in the right orbit.multiple comminuted facial fractures with posterior impaction, involving the vomer, nasal bones and medial maxillary sinus walls.fluid-fluid levels in the axillary sinuses, consistent with hemorrhage.the presence of fluid-fluid levels could suggest a coagulopathic state.

text: comparison was made with the previous ct examination of ___.again multiple facial fractures as well as mandibular fracture are identified.since the previous study there has been internal fixation of the mandibular fracture with plate and screws.the fracture fragments appear to be in apposition.small amount of air is seen in the soft tissues near the mandible.an ng tube is visualized.again extensive facial fractures are seen involving the right zygomatic arch, right maxillary sinus and also the left maxillary sinus.extensive soft tissue changes are seen in the visualized paranasal sinuses.extensive soft tissue edema and soft tissue stranding is identified as before.

text: multiple fractures are identified: fracture is seen along petrous portion of the right temporal bone.there are extensive fractures involving both maxillary sinus with fractures identified within the bilateral medial/ lateral and right anterior wall.there is orbital involvement with fracture identifed through the bilateral lateral and inferior orbital wall.fracture is also identified through right temporal process and bilateral medial/lateral pterygoid plates.in addition there is a fracture of the left nasal bone and left anterior mandible.air-fluid levels are seen throughout bilateral maxillary and sphenoid sinuses as well as extensive subcutaneous edema and bilateral periorbital edema.
summary: extensive fractures involving the sinuses and orbits are most consistent with lefort type 3 fracture.final attending comment: in addition to above: right lefort 1 and bilateral lefort 2 fractures are also seen.there is likely fracture of the left sphenoid sinus with a fluid level and opacification of the left petrous temporal bone and middle ear without definite fracture seen.there is a fracture of the right temporal bone.there is a small extraconal hematoma in the right inferior orbit without mass effect.

text: there is a nondisplaced linear fracture in the left frontal bone extending inferiorly through the anterior and posterior walls of the left frontal sinus into the medial wall of the left orbit.fluid and air are seen within the left sinus likely secondary to trauma and there is a tiny focus of pneumocephalus anterior to the left frontal lobe (series 2, image 17).there is no posterior retropulsion of the fracture fragments.within the right orbit there is fracture of the superior orbital roof posteriorly as well as inferior and lateral orbital walls.inferior displacement of a superior fracture fragment compresses upon the superior rectus muscle.there is no inferior herniation of the orbital contents.the left orbital roof is fractured medially.there is additional fracture of the left medial and inferior orbital walls.there is no inferior herniation of the orbital contents.there is a left superior orbit extraconal hematoma without significant mass effect on the globe.comminuted fracture is also seen within the nasal bone and septum extending to the nasal spine.the lateral, medial, and anterior walls of both maxillary sinuses are fractured.comminuted fractures are also seen within ethmoid air cells.there are comminuted fractures of both pterygoid plates.there is fracture of the anterior right zygomatic arch.fracture of the maxilla and incisors and canine teeth.subcutaneous tissues demonstrate marked swelling anterior to the left frontal bone extending inferiorly to the level of the left orbit.fluid representing hemorrhage is seen in the frontal, ethmoid, and maxillary sinuses.there is mucosal thickening of the sphenoid sinus.
summary: left frontal nondisplaced fracture extending through the anterior and posterior walls of the left frontal sinus.single focus of pneumocephalus in the left frontal lobe.multiple comminuted fractures of the orbital walls.right superior orbital wall fracture fragment is displaced inferiorly and compresses upon the superior rectus muscle.although orbits appear intact orbital injury cannot be excluded on this examination.there is a left superior orbit extraconal hematoma without significant mass effect on the globe.comminuted nasal bone fracture involving the nasal septum and nasal spine.comminuted fractures of the maxillary sinuses and ethmoid air cells.comminuted maxilla fracture.fracture through the pterygoid plates.findings discussed with dr.___ on ___.

text: there are extensive skull base fractures, extending from the floor of the left middle cranial fossa, through the clivus and the foramen magnum, and extending into the left carotid canal and also involving the medial wall of the sphenoid sinus.there are small foci of air within the carotid canal, and surrounding the carotid artery.small foci of pneumocephalus are also seen in the inferior temporal lobe.additional fractures are seen through the left zygomatic arch, the left lateral orbital wall, and the left orbital floor, as well as the anterior, medial, and lateral walls of the left maxillary sinus.there is no definite herniation of any orbital contents.the left maxillary sinus, nasoethmoid air cells, and sphenoid sinus are all at least partially opacified with blood.right mastoid air cells are partially opacified, and right temporal bone fracture is seen, but only partially visualized on current study.
summary: extensive skull base fractures involving the clivus, foramen magnum, and extending into the left carotid canal.vascular injury cannot be excluded, and would be best evaluated with mra.left orbital fractures, without definite herniation of any orbital contents.left zygomatic arch fracture.extensive left maxillary sinus fractures.right temporal bone fracture, incompletely imaged on this study.

text: there are extensive bilateral facial bone fractures.there are fractures of the nasal bones bilaterally as well as of the nasal septum and comminution of the anterior nasal spine.regarding the right maxillary sinus, there is a minimally.depressed fracture of the anterior wall.there are multiple fractures of the lateral, medial, and posterior walls of the left maxillary sinus, which is nearly completely opacified, likely by hemorrhagic contents.there is a fracture through the left orbital floor which extends through the infraorbital nerve canal with intraorbital gas.no entrapment of orbital contents in the floor fracture is seen.there are two nondisplaced fractures of the left zygomatic arch as well as a comminuted fracture of the lateral orbital wall on the left.the left globe is intact.however, there is extensive gas anterior to the left globe.the left globe is noted to be somewhat proptotic.on the right, there is a probable hairline fracture of the right orbital floor without opacification of the maxillary sinus.there is no fracture through the pterygoid plates.there is extensive soft tissue swelling overlying the entire face.there is no mandibular fracture noted.
summary: extensive bilateral facial bone fractures, left greater than right as described above.

text: there is a blowout fracture of the left lamina papyracea.there is no evidence of entrapment of the medial rectus musculature.a small amount of air is present within the orbital fat adjacent to the fracture site.no fracture fragments are identified within the orbit.there is opacification of multiple ethmoid air cells, consistent with either inflammatory mucosal thickening, as well as hemorrhage.there is complete opacification of the right maxillary sinusm, without evidence of fracture.there is absence of right ostiomeatal complex- has there been prior surgery in this locale? this information needs to be correlated clinically.there is thickening of the right maxillary sinus wall, consistent with chronic inflammatory sinus disease.of probable similar etiology is loss of aeration of the nasal cavity bilaterally, due to soft tissue opacification.there is an acute minimally displaced fracture of the left occipital condyle (400b:66), and minimally displaced fracture of the right occipital condyle (400b:63).
summary: acute blowout fracture of the left lamina papyracea, with inflammatory mucosal thickening and/or hemorrhage within multiple ethmoid air cells.there is no evidence of medial rectus muscle entrapment.acute minimally displaced fractures of bilateral occipital condyles.findings consistent with chronic right maxillary sinus disease.please see above comments re: right ostiomeatal complex- if there has been no prior surgery, the loss of visualization of the bony structures in this locale requires further evaluation to exclude fungal or neoplastic disease.

text: there are minimal amounts of polypoid mucosal thickening throughout the maxillary sinuses bilaterally.there is complete opacification of both the sides of the frontal sinus with scattered opacities throughout the ethmoid sinus air cells.the anterior wall of the frontal sinus is fragmented as on numerous prior exams.these represent postoperative changes on the prior studies dating back to ___.status post repair of a gunshot wound to the face.there is nasal packing within the anterior nasal cavity.nasal bone fractures and fragmentation of the anterior wall of the right maxillary sinus are also noted, similar to prior examinations.there are numerous tiny metallic foreign bodies within the soft tissues overlying the anterior right maxillary wall.metallic foreign bodies are also noted within the soft tissues deep to the nasolabial folds bilaterally.there is another tiny metallic foreign body within the anterior wall of the right maxillary sinus.these are all consistent with the prior bullet fragments.there are extensive atherosclerotic calcifications within the cavernous portions of both internal carotid arteries.no metallic foreign bodies are present in the region of the globes.
summary: no change from prior examinations in the defects of the frontal sinus as well as the fragmentation in the right maxillary sinus and the nasal packing.numerous metallic foreign bodies within the soft tissues anterior to the right maxillary sinus as well as within the soft tissues deep to both nasolabial folds.no radiopaque foreign body is noted in the proximity to the globes.

text: the inflammatory change involving the lateral aspect of the left orbit, as well as the soft tissues surrounding the left orbit appear slightly reduced in extent, compared to the prior study.no drainable fluid collections are identified, allowing for the limitations of a non-contrast ct scanning technique.there has been an increase in the opacification of the left maxillary sinus compared to the prior study.there remains mucosal thickening of several ethmoid air cells.the frontal and sphenoid air cells as well as the mastoid air cells remain clear.there has been surgery, with hardware again seen along the left mandibular ramus.there remains a very irregular appearance of the temporomandibular joint on the left, particularly on the left condylar head, which is unchanged, and may be postoperative, although ongoing infection in this area needs to be considered.the temporomandibular articulation on the left is very distorted.the right temporomandibular joint appears unremarkable.although this study was not designed to assess intracranial structures, the visualized brain parenchyma appears grossly unremarkable.there are several enlarged left cervical lymph nodes, as before.
summary: left orbital and periorbital inflammatory changes, slightly less extensive, compared to the prior study.there is an increase in the opacification of the left maxillary sinus.irregular left temporomandibular joint, with evidence of prior surgery in this region.there has been no change since the prior study.see above report for additional discussion.

text: there is opacification of majority of the mastoid air cells on the right.there is no evidence of osseous destruction.there is a mucosal thickening/fluid in the right middle ear, consistent with acute otitis media.there is mild mucosal thickening involving frontal sinus.there are air fluid levels and mucosal thickening in the maxillary sinuses bilaterally, left greater than right.there is opacification of several ethmoid air cells, and mucosal thickening in the frontal sinus.there is mild mucosal thickening involving the sphenoid sinus.the ostiomeatal units are not patent bilaterally.lamina papyracea is intact.

text: there is proptosis of the left eye, tautness of the left optic nerve, and non/minimally displaced fractures through the left zygomatic bone, left superior maxillary body/inferior orbit wall and rim, left sphenoid ___, left lamina papyracea, and left frontal skull .some subgaleal air is seen overlying the nondisplaced skull fracture.a tiny amount of pneumocephalus is identified.while there is mucosal thickening within the maxillary sinuses and opacification of ethmoid air cells, there are no air-fluid levels in the maxillary sinus.mastoid air cells appear well aerated.external auditory canals are patent.middle ear cavities appear normal.petrous apices are not pneumatized.the patient is intubated.

text: there are minimally displaced fractures involving the nasal bones with no definite septal involvement identified.there is reidentification of a fracture through the right frontal bone with extension into the right frontal sinuses.there is a fracture through the right lamina papyracea with extension to the orbital roof and orbital floor with orbital emphysema identified.no depression of the floor or herniation of intraorbital contents is identified.note is also made of a minimally displaced fracture through the right zygoma.the left lamina papyracea appears intact, however, there are minimally displaced fractures involving the left maxillary bone with fractures through the floor, anterior, medial and lateral walls of the left maxillary sinus.the pterygoid plates and mandibles appear unremarkable.there are comminuted fractures involving the walls of the sphenoid sinuses (right greater than left side).extensive subcutaneous emphysema is noted within the left parapharyngeal space extending into the mandibular fossa with no definite surrounding fracture identified or obvious fracture through the carotid canal, however, mri may be obtained for better evaluation once the patient is clinically stable.there is hyperdense fluid located within the middle ear cavities bilaterally (left greater than right) with opacification of the left mastoid air cells.hyperdense fluid is noted through all the paranasal sinuses consistent with hematoma.globes are intact with no intraconal hematomas identified.patient is again noted to be intubated with nasogastric tube passing through the oral cavity.upper cervical spine appears unremarkable.soft tissue findings are described on ct from same day with soft tissues within the neck appearing unremarkable.
summary: multiple facial fractures with fractures involving the right zygomatic arch, right frontal bone extending into the right frontal sinus, right lamina papyracea extending into the right orbital roof and orbital floor, and right maxillary sinus lateral wall.fractures involving the left maxilla, and anterior, lateral, and inferior medial walls of the maxilarry sinus with extensive left-sided subcutaneous emphysema and opacification of the left mastoid air cells and the left middle ear cavity.minimally displaced nasal bone fractures with no apparent septal involvement.multiple minimally displaced fractures involving the sphenoid sinus with no compression of the optic nerves identified.intact globes without intraconal hematoma.

text: no fracture is appreciated.there is no opacification or air-fluid levels within the sinuses.upper cervical spine is intact.the skull base is intact.mastoid processes are normally pneumatized and aerated.the known large right subgaleal hematoma is partially imaged on this study.small amount of left temporal subarachnoid blood is suboptimally seen.

text: there is extensive soft tissue injury in the extracalvarial soft tissues of the forehead favoring the left and extending the subcutaneous emphysema over the preseptal soft tissues of the left orbit.the more distal caudal extent of this process extends over the left maxilla.despite the extensive subcutaneous air, no embedded radiopaque foreign bodies are identified.there is significant left exophthalmus.the globe is intact with lens in place.stranding is noted in the intraconal retrobulbar soft tissues.scattered air is seen medially in the extraconal retrobulbar soft tissues.there is a fracture through the outer table of the left frontal sinus.fracture extends inferiorly to the nasofrontal suture.there is extensively comminuted fracture of the bilateral nasal bones with slight inward deviation.the nasal septum is fractured in multiple places.there is likely nondisplaced fracture involving the medial wall of the right orbit.this is suspected due to small locules of air seen medially in the extraconal retrobulbar soft tissues of the right orbit.there is a more obvious nondisplaced fracture involving the medial wall of the left orbit.displaced fracture is seen in the inferior wall, although there is no herniation of intraorbital contents or impingement on rectus muscles seen.rectus muscles demonstrate normal morphology and orientation.there are fractures of the medial walls of both maxillary sinuses.an air- fluid level is noted in the right maxillary sinus likely due to hemorrhage.more chronic mucosal thickening is seen in the left maxillary sinus.a lobulated soft tissue mass is noted in the left sphenoid sinus, likely mucus retention cyst versus polyp.scattered opacification of the ethmoid air cells is seen.small air-fluid levels are seen in the right frontal sinus.the zygomatic arches, pterygoid plates, and mandible are intact without evidence of fracture.mandibular condyles are appropriately located.patient has orogastric and endotracheal tubes present.

text: a nasogastric and endotracheal tube are seen in place; their tips are not visualized.there is moderate mucosal thickening within the ethmoid and sphenoid sinuses.with aerosolized secretions seen in the maxillary sinuses, right greater than left.there is opacification of several mastoid air cells bilaterally.the frontal sinus air cells are well aerated.the ostiomeatal units are opacified by soft tissue density, likely mucosal thickening the nasal septum deviates to the left, with a large nasal septal spur.the cribriform plates are equal in height.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.the sphenoid septum is multipartite and inserts on the left carotid groove.there is no evidence of osseous destruction.

text: the paranasal sinuses are clear and there is no evidence of underlying dental abscess.however, there are lucencies surrounding the roots of a right mandibular molar, and a left incisor.these may reflect dentla infection.soft tissues in these areas are partialy obscured by dental artifacts.the right ostiomeatal unit appears patent; however, there is mild thickening noted along the left ostiomeatal unit.the lamina papyracea appears intact and the nasal septum is noted to be mildly deviated towards the left.the cribriform plates are equal in height and there is unchanged appearance to calcification within the carotid vessels and the siphons bilaterally.

text: no fracture is ___.both maxillary sinuses and sphenoidal sinuses and posterior, middle and anterior ethmoidal sinuses appear to be filled with fluid, in part hemorrhagic, since hematocrit effect is seen within this fluid.frontal sinuses are clear.the ostiomeatal complexes appear occluded bilaterally, most likely due to mucosal thickening.the cribriform plates appear intact.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.lamina papyracea appears intact.the nasal septum is in the midline.the sphenoid sinus septum is intact.

text: a fracture through the mid/posterior left zygomatic arch may be old.no additional fractures are identified.the orbital floors, and lamina papyracea are intact.the left globe is preserved, and there is no retro- orbital soft tissue stranding.a large left frontal subgaleal hematoma is again identified, with focal areas of increased density, which may represent acute hemorrhage, calcifications, or retained foreign bodies.hyperdense secretions fill bilateral sphenoid air cell, scattered ethmoid air cells.there are small air-fluid levels in the left frontal and left maxillary sinuses.there are prominent dental caries in the remaining upper incisors.a low-density fluid collection surrounding a left incisor root canal may be related to infection, and clinical correlation is requested.

text: bilateral temporal bone and right occipital bone fractures are better delineated on head ct from clip ___.bilateral nasal bone fractures are comminuted.multiple fractures through the sphenoid bone have fracture fragments that are displaced into the sphenoid air cells.a minimally displaced 3-mm bony fragment projecting into the middle cranial fossa appears to arise from the left posterior clinoid.the roof of the sphenoid sinus is depressed centrally by less than 2 mm.a fracture through the right sphenoid body communicates with the cavernous portion of the carotid canal.a fracture of the sphenoid sinus wall on the left also approaches the left carotid artery.the orbital rims are intact bilaterally.the lamina papyracea is preserved.the globes are intact and other than a small amount of intraorbital air, right greater than left, the retroorbital fat is clear.blood largely filled bilateral sphenoid air cells.scattered ethmoid air cells are also opacified.fluid or blood is layering in bilateral maxillary sinuses, and there is moderate right maxillary sinus mucosal thickening.the mandible and maxillary sinuses are intact.there is no fracture in either zygomatic arch or bone.right frontal pneumocephalus and left temporal parenchymal hemorrhage are better described on corresponding head ct.a tamponading foley catheter is positioned in the patient's oropharynx.prominent subcutaneous emphysema in the soft tissues of the right posterior upper neck is better delineated on the patient's corresponding ct cervical spine.
summary: multiple facial fractures as detailed above.in particular, comminuted sphenoid bone fracture fragments project mainly into the sphenoid sinus.a 3-mm fracture fragment from the left posterior clinoid projects into the middle cranial fossa.a fracture through the right sphenoid body approximates the cavernous portion of the right carotid artery.there are bilateral comminuted nasal bone fractures.the bones around both orbits are intact.an mr examination with axial t1 weighted imaged and mra may be helpful to evaluate possible arterial dissection.

text: there are air-fluid levels in the sphenoid and maxillary sinuses, with complete opacification of the right sphenoid sinus.there is also fluid in the nasal cavity and near-opacification of the ethmoid cells bilaterally with a small air-fluid level in the left frontal sinus.there is no evidence of associated bony destruction.the fluid and soft tissue thickening among the paranasal sinuses is of intermediate density.the patient is intubated with an orogastric tube.the orbits are within normal limits.there are bilateral small areas of relative hypodensity in the nasopharyngeal soft tissues but without well- defined fluid collections.there is a defect in the right orbital floor, presumably due to an old inferior blow out fracture.

text: there are multiple foci of intracranial hemorrhage, discussed on a report of the head ct of the same day.skull base and facial fractures are discussed here.there are somewhat displaced fractures through the left inferior orbital wall and along the left zygoma at two sites.there is a fracture through the lateral wall of the left orbit.in addition, there is a fracture of the temporal bone.there is a site along the fracture line through the left temporal bone where there is a small depressed fragment is present, pushed in by 5 mm.air adjacent to this wound suggest a penetrating injury.there are also multiple comminuted fractures with displacement and impaction involving the sphenoid bone including partial collapse and inferior impaction of the roof of the sphenoid with fracture lines extending to the sella and region of the cavernous sinus.there is a left sided fracture of the floor of the anterior cranial fossa with extension into the left ethmoid air cells.there is also posterior impaction of fragments involving lateral walls of the sphenoid sinus which may impinge on the optic nerves along the optic canals.the sphenoid sinus fractures are adjacent to the carotid arteries bilaterally, raising the possibility of arterial injury.fracture lines extend into the left pyramidal process of the sphenoid and along the medial and lateral pterygoid plates.the intraorbital contents appear preserved.
summary: complex facial and skull base fractures as described, including inferior impaction of the roof of the sphenoid, with fracture lines extending to the area of the cavernous sinus and fragments perhaps impinging on the optic struts.ct angiography could be helpful to assess the cavernous carotid arteries and the circle of ___, as fracture lines extend up to the caverous sinus region.cta was suggested to dr.___ later on the same morning, if clinically indicated.short interval ct follow- up is also recommended for extensive intracranial hemorrhages.

text: there are fractures of the medial, inferior, and lateral walls of the left orbit.there is fluid accumulation within the left maxillary sinus , frontal, sphenoid and ethmoid sinuses, with no other evidence of fracture within the bony walls of the sinus.the right maxillary sinus, right ethmoid sinus, and right frontal sinus have normal appearance.the cribriform plates are not equal in height.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.the nasal septum is in midline.

text: there are mild amounts of mucosal thickening within the maxillary sinuses bilaterally.the ostiomeatal complexes are obstructed bilaterally.there are scattered opacities in the ethmoid sinus air cells with no osseous erosions.there is a small amount of soft tissue opacity near the frontoethmoidal recesses bilaterally.the sphenoid sinuses are small with aerosolized secretions in the left sphenoid sinus.small amounts of mucosal thickening are also present.there is a 1-cm soft tissue lesion posterior to the middle turbinate on the right projecting posteriorly.this may represent a small polyp.direct visualization is recommended.the olfactory fossa is ___ type 2 bilaterally.

text: compared to 10 days prior, there has been improvement in extensive sinus opacification.previously seen air-fluid levels in the maxillary and sphenoid sinuses have resolved with mild residual mucosal thickening in the maxillary sinuses.moderate ethmoid sinus opacification persists as well as near complete opacification of the sphenoid sinus.the frontal sinuses are clear.mastoid air cells continue to be nearly completely opacified.the orbits are within normal limits.there is no evidence of associated bony destruction.

text: there is mild-to-moderate thickening of the frontal sinuses.there is moderate thickening of the ethmoid sinuses.there is mild-to-moderate polypoid thickening of the maxillary sinuses.there is mild-to-moderate thickening of the left side of the sphenoid sinus.there is no evidence of air-fluid level or bone destruction.the nasal septum deviates to the left.the cribriform plates are symmetric in height.the ostiomeatal units are soft tissue occluded.there may have been prior surgery on the left maxillary sinus.clinical correlation advised.anterior clinoids are not pneumatized.the sphenoid septum does not insert on either carotid groove.

text: there is an ng tube within the right nasal cavity extending into the nasopharynx.there is an et tube positioned within the oropharynx.the paranasal sinuses are well aerated.no soft tissue calcification is seen within the maxillary or frontal sinus, and the sphenoid and ethmoid air cells are well aerated.there is a ___ bullosa within the right middle turbinate.the ostiomeatal units are patent bilaterally.the right anterior clinoid process is pneumatized.there is a multipartite sphenoid septum.the soft tissue structures are within normal limits.

text: there is a fluid collection with rim enhancement measuring approximately 30 mm ap x 26 mm transverse x 20 mm cephalocaudad in the floor of the mouth interpose between the geniohyoid muscles superiorly and the mylohyoid muscle inferiorly.the collection has one small locule of internal air.extensive inflammatory reaction is noted adjacent to the collection.small submental lymph nodes are seen in the regionally.there is a linear defect approximately 11 mm deep in the superficial submental soft tissues poitning towards the anterior margin of the collection suggestive of a possible sinus tract, although complete communication is not demonstrated.there is internal high attenuation material of unknown etiology, which may represent an imbedded foreign body.there is no evidence of bony erosion or other involvement.the first premolar on the right is absent, likely related to the recent extraction.prominent 8 mm short axis lymph nodes are noted throughout the bilateral jugulodigastric lymph node chains.no definite cervical lymph adenopathy is identified.vessels are patent.the submandibular, parotid, and thyroid glands image normally.the airway is widely patent.the epiglottis and aryepiglottic folds are within normal limits.the included paranasal sinuses are clear.likewise, no fluid is seen in the mastoid air cells or the middle ear cavities.

text: there is mucosal thickening with fluid and aerosolized secretions involving the left side of the sphenoid sinus (near-complete opacification), right posterior ethmoids, left maxillary sinus (mild to moderate).this appearance is consistent with acute sinusitis.polypoidal mucosal thickening as well as retention cysts versus polyps are noted in bilateral maxillary sinuses, the largest in the right maxillary sinus measures 2.3 cm in the transverse diameter.mucosal thickening is noted around osteomeatal units bilaterally with mild occlusion on the left side.the nasal septum is unremarkable.the cribriform plates are of equal height.bilateral laminae papyracea intact.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.left maxillary dental bone graft is noted.

text: there are fractures of medial and lateral pterygoid plates bilaterally, medial lateral and anterior maxillary sinus walls bilaterally, comminuted fracture of the nasal septum, inferior and medial orbital walls bilaterally.there is a fracture across the nasal bridge just distal to the nasal sutures, this is nondisplaced.extensively comminuted fractures of the nasal bones.given the involvement across the nasal bridge and the medial orbital walls, bilateral ___-orbital ethmoid fractures not excluded.there is not extensive comminution, so type i versus unlikely type ii fractures suspected.zygomatic arches and temporal bones are intact.there is no mandibular fracture.the fracture involving the right inferior orbital wall extends through the inferior orbital canal.there is blood within the imaged paranasal sinuses.there is subcutaneous emphysema.bilateral preseptal hematomas are present.the globes are intact.soft tissue attenuation is present in both internal auditory canals, however no temporal bone fracture is seen.correlate clinically with presence of hemotympanum.

text: no comparisons are available.there are comminuted depressed fractures of the anterior walls of the maxillary sinuses bilaterally, worse on the right side.the fractures involve the infraorbital canal on the right.there is also extension to the inferior wall of the orbits bilaterally; bony fragment on the right extending superiorly into the orbit.herniation of orbital fat into the depressed fractures bilaterally but worse on the left side.the fracture fragments are abutting the inferior rectus muscle on the right.fractures of the posterolateral wall of the right maxillary sinus are also seen.there are fractures of the nasal processes of the maxilla bilaterally.fractures of the medial walls of the maxillary sinuses bilaterally are seen.there is comminuted fractures of the nasal bones and the nasal bridge, extending to involve the anterior ethmoid air cells.fixation plate and screws are seen over the left nasal bridge as well as along the inferior anterior wall of the right maxillary sinus.hemorrhage is seen within the maxillary sinuses, ethmoid air cells, and there is mucosal thickening involving the sphenoid and right frontal sinus.the globes are intact.there is no intraorbital hemorrhage.no intracranial abnormalities are seen.there is minimal soft tissue density within the retroantral fat suggestive of hemorrhage.

text: there is an oblique nondisplaced, nondepressed fracture extending from an area of extensive deep laceration along the lateral left forehead to the lateral aspect of the left superior orbit and supraorbital ridge.a component of the fracture appears to traverse the posterior aspect of the orbital roof extending to the anterior cranial fossa and the more lateral left posterior ethmoid air cells.there may be nondisplaced fracture extending along the medial orbital wall as well.the inferior orbital wall appears intact.bilateral globes are intact with lenses in place.no definitive fracture is identified through the maxillary sinus, although minimal layering high-attenuation fluid is noted, likely blood.this is superimposed upon more chronic mucosal thickening which is seen here and elsewhere throughout the paranasal sinuses.the mastoid air cells are clear with no definite temporal bone involvement noted.likewise, the zygomatic arches and pterygoid plates are intact.cortical screws are present in both mandibular angles.the mandibular condyles are anteriorly subluxed.there is extensive lytic destruction with bony remodeling along the left mandibular ramus.heterotopic ossification is noted within the soft tissues anterior to the mandible left of midline.these findings are consistent with known history of an oral cancer.there is marked heterogeneity of the tongue which is difficult to further assess given the lack of iv contrast.however, this is most highly consistent with tumoral involvement.no prior exams are available to attempt to assess for progression or interval change.incidental note is made of extensive calcification at the bilateral carotid siphons.
summary: there is a nondisplaced, nondepressed left frontal bone fracture extending over the left orbit terminating within the anterior cranial fossa and left ethmoid air cells.this has introduced retroorbital extraconal air.the globe itself is intact with lens in place.the intraconal soft tissues are unremarkable.no clear fracture of the left maxillary sinus is evident, although there is likely internal blood.non-displaced fracture cannot be excluded.findings most consistent with invasive cancer involving the left mandibular ramus.heterogeneous soft tissue in the region of the tongue suspicious for the apparently known tumor.comparison study not available to assess for recurrence versus progression versus residual tumor.also limited by lack of iv contrast.

text: the study is compared with the concurrent ct examination of the head.there is extensive edema and hemorrhage in the right frontal scalp soft tissues.this is associated with an oblique-sagittal fracture traversing the right fronto-ethmoidal complex, obliquely, which appears to traverse the ethmoid air cells, exiting at the anterior lateral wall of the contralateral sphenoid sinus, in the region of the left orbital apex, which does not appear significantly narrowed.a second paramedian, sagittally-oriented fracture component exits dorsally at the posterior wall of the right sphenoid sinus, in the region of the anterior most aspect of the right carotid canal.additional fracture components involve the anterior, lateral and medial walls of the left maxillary sinus, with displaced anterior fragment and complete opacification of the sinus.a major longitudinally-oriented fracture also involves the left lateral aspect of the hard palate and that alveolar ridge, with significant distraction.there are also fractures of the lateral and medial pterygoid plates, bilaterally, extending into the bilateral pterygoid processes.the continuation of the right sphenoid sinus sagittal fracture continues dorsally and caudally through the clivus, where it appears to terminate in the anterior aspect of the horizontal portion of the ipsilateral carotid canal.finally, there is a markedly displaced left parasymphyseal fracture of the mandible with significant distraction of the fracture fragments, associated with similarly distracted and overriding fracture of the left mandibular angle and ramus.
summary: numerous facial, sinus, maxillary, skull base and mandibular fractures, as outlined above, with involvement of the right carotid canal and left orbital apex.the limited included portion of the upper cervical spine appears intact; please see separately dictated report of that study.findings discussed with trauma surgery team.

text: nasogastric tube is in place.again appreciated are fracture deformities of the left zygomatic arch, the left lateral orbital wall, and the left maxillary sinus wall, most likely representing old trauma.no new fractures are identified.again seen is the region of hypodensity in the right frontal cortex and subcortical white matter, consistent with remote infarction or sequela of prior traumatic injury.otherwise, there is minimal mucosal thickening in the ethmoid, sphenoid, and maxillary air cells.the mastoid air cells are well aerated, as are the frontal sinuses.there is also mucosal thickening in the left ostiomeatal units, without obstruction.the cribriform plates are intact.the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.the lamina papyracea are intact.the nasal septum is slightly deviated to the left, but is intact.

text: the patient is intubated.there is near complete opacification of all of the visualized paranasal sinuses and of the mastoid air cells.there is only partial aeration of the left frontal sinus.frontal sinus demonstrates no aerosolization.an endotracheal tube passes through the left naris.an orogastric tube is present.the mastoid air cells are poorly pneumatized, although there is also partial opacification of the bilateral mastoid air cells.visualized portions of the brain are unremarkable.

text: comparison is made to a prior ct of the sinuses from ___.there is thickening of the dermis and subcutaneous stranding along the right face extending from the inferior margin of the right eye to the right cheek at the level of the maxillary dental row.the right inferior eyelid is thickened, but there is no evidence for post- septal involvement.the soft tissue density is abutting right masseter and the right zygomaticus, with obscuration of the adjacent fat planes, but muscle architecture is normal.involvement of these muscles cannot definitively be excluded.the right stensen's duct appears asymmetrically enlarged, and involvement by tumor cannot be excluded.there is no osseous erosion.no suspicious lesions are identified.the visualized paranasal sinuses are clear.a few of the left mastoid air cells are opacified.no abnormality of the nasopharynx is seen.the exact margins of the tumor are difficult to evaluate, but the subcutaneous soft tissue stranding extends 11 cm in craniocaudal dimension.there is minimal soft tissue stranding of the subcutaneous fat of the left cheek.fatty atrophy of the submandibular glands are seen bilaterally.cataract surgical changes of the globes are seen bilaterally.minimal degenerative change of the right tmj is noted.there are degenerative changes of the visualized upper cervical spine with moderate to severe left foraminal stenoses at c2/3 and c3/4.

text: although not tailored for evaluation of the brain parenchyma, extensive contusions in the anterior frontal lobes have a similar appearance.there is a small amount of subdural hemorrhage layering over the posterior falx and tentorium bilaterally.a small left frontal subdural hematoma appears unchanged.diffuse bilateral foci of subarachnoid hemorrhage have likely decreased in extent.the patient is status post cranioplasty and there is persistent pneumocephalus and depression of the posterior wall of the left frontal sinus, resulting in communication between the left frontal sinus and adjacent intracranial space.the pneumocepahlus and extraaxial fluid density subjacent to the cranioplasty appears to be external to the dura.there is soft tissue density within the left frontal sinus with a tubular air containing structure likely representing surgical material.multiple additional fractures including those extending through the ethmoid septa, sphenoid sinus, nasal bone, right maxillary sinus, and right occipital condyle are again seen.hemorrhage and fluid within the paranasal sinuses and nasal cavity is similar in extent.there is partial opacification of the mastoid air cells, which is new.

text: there is a comminuted fracture through the inferior left orbital wall with a small soft-tissue density in the inferior orbit.the inferior rectus muscle is normal in size and distinct from this opacity.the globes appear intact and no retrobulbar hematoma is identified.calcifications are noted in the posterosuperior right globe of unclear etiology.minimally displaced fractures are also seen through the lateral and medial walls of the left maxillary sinus as well as the body of the left maxilla, anterior left zygomatic bone, left maxillary spine, and lateral wall of the left orbit.the mandible and temporomandibular joints appear unremarkable.there is opacification of the left maxillary sinus with high- density material, presumably hemorrhage.the frontal and ethmoid sinuses are partially opacified.mastoid air cells, right maxillary sinus and sphenoid sinus are clear.there are multiple hyperdense foci overlying the frontal soft tissues which may represent retained foreign bodies.there is moderate preseptal swelling and subcutaneous emphysema.

text: there are comminuted fractures through the anterior, posterior, inferior and medial walls of the right maxillary sinus.there are comminuted fractures of the medial and lateral right pterygoid plates.there is a mildly displaced fracture of the left zygomatic arch.there is a nondisplaced fracture of the right frontal bone which extends into the right temporal bone.there are comminuted fractures of the nasal bone and medial wall of the left orbit.there is extensive hemorrhage throughout the paranasal sinuses.there is significant soft tissue swelling and subcutaneous emphysema of the face and forehead, right greater than left.the globes appear intact.

text: there are acute fractures involving the right lamina papyracea, right nasal spine, right inferior orbital floor, and right anterior maxillary sinus wall which is minimally displaced.there is apparent extension of the nasal fracture to involve the septum which appears deviated leftward.there is associated air-fluid levels and opacification of the right maxillary sinus, nasal cavity, and ethmoid air cells likely consistent with a combination of mucosal thickening and blood.a small polyp or mucous retention cyst is noted within the left frontal sinus.in the region of the right medial orbital wall (lamina papyracea), there is a slight irregularity to the medial rectus muscles with herniation of intraorbital fat which may reflect underlying muscle entrapment.areas of air pockets are noted extraconally within the right orbital cavity.the globes appearing intact bilaterally.no other acute fractures are identified.diffuse soft tissue swelling is noted anterior to the nose.incidental note is made of pneumatization of the left petrous apex.
